<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riley Pitches Academy for Teachers  </HEADLINE>
By ARLENE LEVINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A ''West Point for principals'' is one solution
U.S. Education Secretary Richard Riley proposes to solve a looming
shortage of school administrators.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to be delivered Friday at Columbia University's
Teachers College, Riley also pitched the Clinton administration's
call for a $40 million investment in state or regional training for
school leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The tools of school reform need leaders to put them to use, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the school and district levels,'' Riley said in prepared
remarks, ''someone needs to nurture, engage and orchestrate the
teachers, parents, staff, community and students to use these tools
well and work as teams.''
</P>
<P>
   He was to speak at a daylong National Conference on School
Leadership sponsored by the nonprofit Wallace-Reader's Digest
Funds, which promote education.
</P>
<P>
   There is constant demand for people to run the nation's more
than 125,000 public schools, and a turnover of at least 40 percent
is forecast for the nation's principals in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The task is not simply to cultivate a new generation of
administrators, but to find candidates who want the job.
</P>
<P>
   While teacher quality -- and quantity -- has drawn lots of
attention, only recently has the short supply of administrators
become evident, partly because there's no lack of certified
professionals. Many teachers return to graduate school to boost
their qualifications and salaries. They end up with licenses to
work as principals, but never do.
</P>
<P>
   Alarms began to be sounded in recent years when superintendents
began reporting that instead of the 70 applicants they sifted
through to fill principal slots, they were getting five, 10, maybe
15, said Gerald Tirozzi, executive director of the National
Association of Secondary School Principals.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't reform public education one classroom at a time,''
Tirozzi said from his office in Reston, Va. ''Without strong
leaders in the schools, you can't have school reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers blame a host of reasons for lack of interest in the
top school jobs: long hours, increasing accountability for student
performance, more responsibility for school safety, pay not much
better than teachers make, the lure of better pay in other careers.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's speech noted some of these issues. He lauded efforts to
recruit leaders from outside education, and a North Carolina
scholarship-loan program where newly minted principals pay off
their debt by serving as a principal or assistant principal in a
public school.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of the School Leadership Institute. Proposed in the
federal education budget now before Congress, the institute would
create 20 state or regional centers to train 10,000 school
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   The role of administrator needs to be redefined as well, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the future,'' Riley said, ''if we are still scrambling for
principals and superintendents and then asking them to take on
Herculean tasks, that leave them little time to focus on the
curriculum and improving instruction, then we will have failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said if the institute comes to fruition, thought should be
given to creating a ''National Academy for School Leadership'' akin
to West Point. ''Good schools are vital to our prosperity and our
national security,'' Riley said. A national academy could make
fostering school leaders a national priority.
</P>
<P>
   He also endorsed a plan under way by national principals and
superintendents groups to set national standards for school
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ed.gov
</P>
<P>
   http://www.wallacefunds.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.principals.org
</P>
</TEXT>
