<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.Deploys Warship in East Timor  </HEADLINE>
By HEATHER PATERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Backed by four U.S. Navy ships, hundreds
of heavily armed Marines moved onto the convulsed island of East
Timor Friday to deliver humanitarian aid -- but ready to defend
against any threat by militia gangs.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military operation comes less than a week after the
militias killed three U.N. aid workers in neighboring West Timor.
Other gangs have killed two U.N. peacekeepers in East Timor in
recent clashes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to provide aid and we don't want anyone getting in our
way,'' said Marine spokesman Lt. Jeff Landis, who was on the scene.
''Any militia activity that goes on in our presence, we won't
tolerate. We will basically get the aid to where it needs to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Landis said about 4,000 troops arrived Thursday aboard the
ships, which include the guided missile carrier USS Bunker Hill and
three amphibious vessels: USS Tarawa, Delouth and Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of those troops spent several hours Thursday ferrying
tons of building materials and food from the ships to the island.
The aid was provided to humanitarian groups, which will distribute
it to the island's needy.
</P>
<P>
   The troops spent Thursday night aboard their vessels and resumed
their task on Friday. Landis said they would leave East Timor
waters on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Marine spokesman Lt. David Nethers said the
troops -- members of the 13th Marine Expeditionary Unit, based at
Camp Pendleton, Calif. -- would defend aid workers and ''assess the
threat and take appropriate precautionary measures.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. navy ships have brought in aid to East Timor several times
in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Landis said that a warship was now needed to protect
the aid and the Marines delivering it from possible militia attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''If fired upon we are allowed to fire back in kind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The militias are the same gangs who opposed East Timor's
independence from Indonesian rule last year.
</P>
<P>
   At that time they went on a rampage, killing hundreds and
destroying thousands of buildings. The mayhem only ended when
international peacekeepers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the militias have fled to Indonesian West Timor where
they have used border refugee camps as bases for attacks into East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The Tarawa, with helicopters and Harrier jump jets, is
delivering aid to the capital, Dili.
</P>
<P>
   The Delouth is anchored near the southern border town of Suai,
and the Anchorage and Bunker Hill are off the isolated enclave of
Oecusse. Both Suai and Oecusse have seen rising militia activity in
recent times.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are here for humanitarian reasons and we feel that there's
no reason why we should have to use any force to get the aid
through,'' said Landis, a native of Sunbury, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. aid effort is operating independently of East Timor's
current U.N. administration, which is preparing the territory for
full independence within two years. It is also separate from a U.N.
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really about us trying to lend a hand to the East
Timorese for their transition to independence and help them rebuild
their country, and have a stable government and democracy,'' said
Landis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
