<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, Sept. 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reno To Push for Puerto Rico Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday
the Justice Department will take ''appropriate steps'' to deal with an effort by
residents of Puerto Rico to gain the right to vote in the upcoming presidential
election. A group of residents filed lawsuit in U.S. District Court for Puerto
Rico pushing for the right to vote. The judge hearing the case in August ordered
that Puerto Rico's government ''act with all possible expediency'' to enable
islanders to vote for president as a constitutional right. The Justice
Department filed its appeal Tuesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S.Deploys Warship in East Timor
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor (AP) -- U.S. Navy ships and Marine troops arrived in East
Timor waters Thursday to counter any threat by militia gangs against an aid
mission on the devastated island, a military spokesman said. Last week, militias
killed three U.N. aid workers in neighboring West Timor and other gangs have
killed two U.N. peacekeepers in East Timor in recent clashes. Marine spokesman
Lt. Jeff Landis said about 4,000 troops arrived aboard four U.S. ships. The
vessels were carrying tons of building materials and food for the island
territory. The ships will leave East Timor on Saturday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cruise Ship Criticized for Waste
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) -- Gov. Tony Knowles lambasted the cruise ship industry
Thursday, saying recent tests of the sewage and wastewater dumped by ships show
disgraceful violations of state and federal pollution standards. Preliminary
results found that all 36 samples of treated sewage taken from 12 ships this
summer exceeded federal standards for fecal coliform bacteria, according to the
Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation and the Coast Guard. And more
than 70 percent of samples of gray water -- the unregulated and untreated waste
stream from sinks and showers -- exceeded those standards. Complete results are
pending.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Florence Prompts Watch in Bermuda
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Storm watches were posted Thursday in Bermuda as Tropical Storm
Florence showed signs of swinging away from the southeast United States. The
nearly stationary storm was 535 miles west-southwest of Bermuda at 11 p.m. EDT
Thursday and moving to the southeast at 3 mph with maximum sustained winds of 45
mph. It was expected to begin trekking eastward by Friday. Strong winds and
pounding surf were possible in Bermuda by Friday evening, said forecasters at
the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Accepts Bipartisan Debate Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Giving in after a two-week battle over debates, Republican
George W. Bush agreed Thursday to Democrat Al Gore's demand that they meet in
three prime-time confrontations sponsored by a bipartisan panel. The running
mates will debate once. Americans will see Bush and Gore go head to head on
television Oct. 3 in Boston, Oct. 11 in Winston-Salem, N.C., and Oct. 17 in St.
Louis, with each debate lasting 90 minutes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Boeing To Install New Rudders
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing said Thursday it won't begin installing new rudder
systems on 737 jetliners until 2003 and in the meantime will train pilots how to
handle jammed rudders. The Federal Aviation Administration said Boeing will
design new controls for the rudder, the flap on the vertical tail of the
aircraft that is suspected in a pair of deadly U.S. air crashes in the past
decade. Boeing said the final plan for the upgrades won't be finished until
2003.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Maytag Predicts Lower Earnings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEWTON, Iowa (AP) -- Maytag Corp. said Thursday that second-half results will
be lower than expected because of significant disruptions for retail home
appliances. The company predicted in July that it's full-year earnings-per-share
would be $3.80, but as of late it has downplayed the likelihood of meeting that
estimate. Maytag said Thursday it expects earnings-per-share in the second half
to be down 8 to 10 percent from last year's second half results of $1.74 per
share. Maytag indicated earnings per share in the second half would be uneven,
with third quarter performance expected in the mid-70-cents range and fourth
quarter expectations in the low-to-mid 80 cents range.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 95; Nasdaq Gains 20
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chips fell sharply Thursday on profit-taking and
concerns about the drop in the euro currency, but technology stocks moved higher
for a second straight session. The Dow Jones industrial average closed down
94.71 at 11,087.47. On the NYSE, gainers led advancers by a narrow margain. The
Nasdaq composite index rose 19.97 at 3,913.86.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cardinals Beat Cubs 4-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Pat Hentgen pitched a three-hitter for his first shutout in
more than three years in a 4-0 victory over the Chicago Cubs on Thursday night.
He struck out a season-high nine and walked none for his 10th career shutout,
and first since June 20, 1997 against Baltimore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
