<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florence Prompts Watch in Bermuda  </HEADLINE>
By ADRIAN SAINZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Storm watches were posted Thursday in Bermuda as
Tropical Storm Florence showed signs of swinging away from the
southeast United States.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly stationary storm was 535 miles west-southwest of
Bermuda at 11 p.m. EDT Thursday and moving to the southeast at 3
mph with maximum sustained winds of 45 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It was expected to begin trekking eastward by Friday. Strong
winds and pounding surf were possible in Bermuda by Friday evening,
said forecasters at the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it follows the forecast track, then they will be right on
the edge,'' said Richard Pasch, a hurricane specialist. ''They
could get wind gusts of up above 40 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   Rip currents associated with Florence and blamed for at least
three surf deaths Tuesday in North Carolina were expected to
continue. The body of the third victim, a 23-year-old man who had
been missing since he fell out of a kayak, was recovered Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they do not intend to reopen the two beaches
until Florence, which briefly was a hurricane this week, is no
longer a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a tropical depression formed in the western Caribbean
with a forecast track eventually taking it into the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The depression could remain near Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula
before entering the gulf Friday, said Eric Blake, a hurricane
center meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Hurricane Center: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
