<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton praises wife's debate performance  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - President Clinton raised campaign cash for his
wife's Senate bid Thursday night and said he was proud - and
nervous - watching her first debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I realize now what she went through all those years with me,''
Clinton said. ''Is he going to fall over? Is he going to smile?
Should he slug back? Should he just keep smiling?''
</P>
<P>
   The president, who aides say helped Hillary Rodham Clinton prep
for the debate Wednesday night in Buffalo, N.Y., gave her
performance a thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought she gave a good account of herself in a difficult
and challenging format,'' he said. ''I was very, very proud of
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks as he hauled in some $350,000 for his
her New York Senate bid Thursday night at an intimate dinner party
held in the Washington, D.C., home of his old friend Vernon Jordan
and his Jordan's wife, Ann. Guests were asked to contribute $25,000
or raise $10,000 to feast on salmon, beef and homemade ice cream.
The money goes to New York Senate 2000, a committee set up by the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee to raise soft money for
the first lady's race against Republican Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday night, Clinton helped raise $500,000 for IMPAC
2000 a Democratic group dedicated to the battle of redrawing
congressional lines set to ensue after results of the 2000 Census
are revealed. The group is headed by Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding nostalgic, Clinton marveled Thursday night at not
running for anything for the first tine in 26 years and instead
trying to boost the campaigns of his wife and Vice President Al
Gore, the Democratic presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   He described voting for his wife in Chappaqua, N.Y., as ''the
most amazing experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was happy as a kid as on Christmas morning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''So now my family has a new candidate and my party has a new
leader and I have become cheerleader in chief, and I like it,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also hinted that he might want to turn his fund-raising
skills to a more personal kind of use.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had more millionaires and more billionaires in the last
eight years than any other time in history and I hope the next
administration keeps it going and maybe I can be one of them,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 0030 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000915.0014 </DOCNO>
