<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boy Scout funding in Delaware threatened by ruling on gays  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DOVER, Del. (AP) - The Boy Scouts of America's policy to bar
gays from becoming scout leaders could jeopardize the Delaware
council's funding from the United Way.
</P>
<P>
   United Way of Delaware has considered changing its funding
approach in response to the U.S. Supreme Court's decision to uphold
the Boy Scout's policy, The (Wilmington) News Journal reported in
Friday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, ruling in June on a New Jersey case, refused
to overturn the ban by a 5-4 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The charitable organization's policy for client funding
prohibits giving money to groups that discriminate based on race,
religion, sex, age and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   The change being considered would add sexual orientation to that
policy, a move that could cost the region's Boy Scouts nearly
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''There hasn't been any reason to look at this policy until this
issue came up,'' said Larry Miller, United Way's director of
workplace campaigns and resource development.
</P>
<P>
   The policy has not been updated since 1992, Miller said, but
United Way's executive committee was expected to discuss the issue
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Del-Mar-Va Council of the Boy Scouts of America got about
$490,000 through the United Way this year, said Council Executive
Jim Gentry. That is about a quarter of its annual budget, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the short run, we probably couldn't make it up,'' he said.
''In the worst case, it would hurt our inner-city kids because they
generally have less of their own money to spend on programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The council covers the Delmarva Peninsula and is made up of
eight geographical districts and one overlapping district of
Explorer Scouts. It includes about 25,000 Scouts, ages 7 to 20, and
between 7,000 and 9,000 adult leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
