<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Warns of Milosevic Win  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
warned Thursday that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic may
''steal'' the upcoming presidential election and called on the
Serbian people to monitor the vote count.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, a traditional ally of Serbia, joined the United States
and four other key countries dealing with the former Yugoslavia to
stress they will evaluate the results of the Sept. 24 election ''on
the basis of internationally recognized standards.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Milosevic's supporters broke up the Kosovo
campaign rally of his strongest challenger, the election featured
prominently in Albright's meeting with foreign ministers from the
15-nation European Union and discussions by the six-nation Contact
Group on the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's supporters pelted presidential candidate Vojislav
Kostunica with tomatoes and stones during a rally in the industrial
city of Kosovska Mitrovica on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken law professor, who is leading in the polls, was
bloodied beneath an eye during the melee.
</P>
<P>
   After a lunch with EU foreign ministers, Albright told a news
conference ''we are united in our call for free and fair elections
in Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what is important here is that the opposition in
Serbia continue to work very hard for these elections, which
unfortunately we are concerned that Milosevic will steal,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is important therefore for the international
community and for the Serbian people to be vigilant throughout the
whole process, especially the counting process, so they can expose
what happened and reject the results if the election is stolen,''
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's information minister claimed Wednesday that Western
powers and pro-democracy forces were plotting to overthrow
Milosevic's government by declaring an opposition triumph in the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said there was a discussion Thursday of ways to
increase support for people across Serbia who are demanding a free
and fair election. She did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said afterward that
Yugoslavia has barred independent monitors from the Organization of
Security and Cooperation in Europe from observing the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia is radically polarized between Milosevic's supporters and
opponents of the autocratic ruler of Yugoslavia, which also
encompasses the much smaller republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has promised to release a substantial amount
of aid for Yugoslavia if the democratic opposition wins the
election. The Norwegian government on Wednesday said it would give
Yugoslavia $15 million if Milosevic is ousted. The United States
would also be expected to aid a democratic Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The six-nation Contact Group is made up of the United States,
Russia, France, Britain, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement after their meeting Thursday afternoon, the
ministers said they ''look forward to a democratic Yugoslavia, so
that it can be reintegrated in the international community and play
its rightful part in contributing to the stability of the entire
region.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic sources said putting the word ''democratic'' into
that sentence was difficult, because of concerns by Russia, which
has close cultural and religious ties to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo which has been under U.N. administration since the Serb
withdrawal after last year's 78-day NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
