<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Habitat For Humanity Hits Milestone  </HEADLINE>
By ELLIOTT MINOR
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLAINS, Ga. (AP) -- It took 20 years for Habitat for Humanity to
build its first 50,000 homes. Four years later, the organization --
which uses volunteers to construct houses for low-income families --
is hammering the final nails into its 100,000th home.
</P>
<P>
   The construction push has stretched from a former president's
peanut farm to a restored building in New York's Harlem
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Millard Fuller, a former millionaire who founded the
organization 24 years ago, said the group hopes to raise $5 billion
to build 100,000 more homes in five years. With more than 2,000
affiliates in 68 countries, Habitat completes a home every 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what we're seeing is the emergence of a new social and
religious movement, which is ending poverty housing and
homelessness,'' he said. ''The growth of this work is escalating
tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   With growth has come criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Despite screening of prospective homeowners, financial
counseling and no-interest loans, Habitat has been forced to evict
a few homeowners who fell behind on payments. And since some
Habitat homes are located in poor, high-crime neighborhoods where
land is cheap, a few families have been forced to move.
</P>
<P>
   But those moving into the homes being finished this week have no
complaints. All the families must work on the construction crews to
build up ''sweat equity.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're putting in the finishing touches. This is really
exciting for my family,'' said Colin Baynes, who along with his
wife and 5-year-old son will move next month into the 100,000th
Habitat home in Harlem. ''Every weekend I was here working, putting
in time. It was a shelled-out building.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Habitat is holding its Jimmy Carter Work Project in
which the former president works for one of his favorite charities.
Some 14,000 volunteers are working to provide 22 new homes in New
York, 100 in Jacksonville, Fla., and 35 in and near Plains,
Carter's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   With saws buzzing and hammers tapping, 200 volunteers, including
former pro football player Rosie Grier and Bernice King, daughter
of slain civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr., swarmed over a
building site Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Swatting gnats and sweating in the south Georgia heat, the
workers nailed studs in place, hung sheet rock and painted walls.
</P>
<P>
   The group's 100,001st home, on land where Carter's father grew
peanuts and cotton, will be turned over to Eugene and Michele
Hughley, who are both prison guards.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the best blessing there is to see my daughter grow up in
her own home with her parents,'' Mrs. Hughley said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who turns 76 next month, said the site has special
significance to him because it's where he ''used to pick cotton and
shake peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, have volunteered for the group
since 1984, building homes on Indian reservations and in blighted
urban areas. The former president said human rights means more than
freedom from oppression.
</P>
<P>
   ''Human rights also involves the basic needs of humans for food
and shelter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Habitat for Humanity: http://www.habitat.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
