<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, Sept. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S.Deploys Warship in East Timor
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor (AP) -- U.S. Navy ships and Marine troops arrived in East
Timor waters Thursday to counter any threat by militia gangs against an aid
mission on the devastated island, a military spokesman said. Last week, militias
killed three U.N. aid workers in neighboring West Timor and other gangs have
killed two U.N. peacekeepers in East Timor in recent clashes. Marine spokesman
Lt. Jeff Landis said about 4,000 troops arrived aboard four U.S. ships. The
vessels were carrying tons of building materials and food for the island
territory. The ships will leave East Timor on Saturday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Pushes Celebrity Politicking
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Al Gore pushed celebrity politicking to dizzying heights
Thursday as he traded laughs with TV's David Letterman over rival George W.
Bush's recent goofs, and raised millions with Bette Midler, Paul Simon and
company. Gore, who strode onto Letterman's unpredictable soundstage to the tune
of Prince's ''Kiss,'' booed the talk show host's suggestion that he had an
anti-Clinton motive in mind when he laid a passionate kiss on wife Tipper at the
Democratic National Convention. Reaching out to young voters, Gore met earlier
with 11 twenty-somethings, gathered in the fashionable Westside Cafe Lalo by
daughter Karenna Gore Schiff, 27.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Census: No. of High School Grads Up
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 83 percent of Americans age 25 and older
graduated from high school, and over 25 percent have at least a college degree
-- both record highs according to new Census Bureau statistics. In March 1999,
83.4 percent of Americans 25 and older had high school diplomas, up from 24.5
percent in 1940, the earliest records available, and 77.6 percent in 1990,
Census data being released Friday shows. The percentage of people within the
same age group with a bachelor's degree increased to 25.2 percent, from 4.6
percent in 1940 and 21.3 percent 10 years ago. The statistics are in line with
other studies done on the country's educational attainment, education advocates
said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Palestinian Peace Talks Resume
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Clinton administration renewed its efforts Thursday to
end a deadlock between Israel and the Palestinians over the future of Jerusalem.
Hanging in the balance was a long-sought settlement of their half-century
dispute. The goal, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said, was to find a
formula that the two sides can accept -- a task that has eluded President
Clinton and all other American mediators who tried to find a compromise between
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's demand for sovereignty over East Jerusalem
and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's offer of some local Palestinian control.
Meanwhile, Saudi Arabia's Crown Prince Abdullah backed the Palestinians in
demanding control of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-Military Brass To Endorse Bush
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several retired military commanders, including some
nominated to top posts by President Clinton, plan to endorse Republican George
W. Bush for the presidency, the Bush campaign said Thursday. They include
just-retired Persian Gulf commander Gen. Anthony Zinni; Adm. Jay Johnson, who
retired as head of the Navy this summer; Gen. Ronald R. Fogleman, who resigned
as Air Force Chief in 1997; former Air Force chief Gen. Merrill McPeak; and
former Marine Commandant Gen. Carl Mundy, said Mindy Tucker, speaking for Bush.
She said the endorsements were expected next week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Florence Prompts Watch in Bermuda
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Storm watches were posted Thursday in Bermuda as Tropical Storm
Florence showed signs of swinging away from the southeast United States. The
nearly stationary storm was 535 miles west-southwest of Bermuda at 11 p.m. EDT
Thursday and moving to the southeast at 3 mph with maximum sustained winds of 45
mph. It was expected to begin trekking eastward by Friday. Strong winds and
pounding surf were possible in Bermuda by Friday evening, said forecasters at
the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 95; Nasdaq Gains 20
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 94.71 at
11,087.47. On the NYSE, gainers led advancers by a narrow margain. The Nasdaq
composite index rose 19.97 at 3,913.86.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Red Sox Beat Indians 7-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Pedro Martinez allowed four hits in seven innings to remain
undefeated in his career against the Indians in leading the Boston Red Sox to a
7-4 win. Martinez (17-5) improved to 7-0 in seven regular-season starts against
the Indians. He's also 2-0 against Cleveland in the postseason, and has been
branded Public Enemy No. 1 around Jacobs Field. Carl Everett went 4-for-5 with a
two-run homer and Bichette homered off Charles Nagy (2-5) as the Red Sox moved
within two games of the Indians, who lead the AL wild card race.
</P>
