<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Raises More Than $6M in NYC  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tom Cruise and Paul Newman sent their regrets
while Harrison Ford was a surprise addition when a dazzling lineup
of entertainers showed up at Radio City Music Hall to raise
millions for a Democratic presidential candidate who's been
attacking their industry.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, raking in $6.5 million for his campaign in the Thursday
night event, touched on his criticisms of Hollywood from earlier in
the week, when he warned it must stop peddling excessive violence
to children or, as president, he would seek sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Gore won lame applause at Radio City when he admonished: ''I'll
be straightforward and honest about this. It is wrong to market
inappropriate material to children. I believe this very deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was quick at the fund-raiser to praise assurances from
some entertainment executives that they will act voluntarily to
protect children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's running mate, Sen. Joe Lieberman, took to the massive
lift-equipped stage to joke about his role as the ''opening act for
Bette Midler.''
</P>
<P>
   The frequently bawdy Midler cracked that she would likely be one
of Lieberman's first targets if he becomes vice president.
Lieberman has been a longtime critic of Hollywood vulgarity.
</P>
<P>
   Midler was joined by music heavyweights such as Jimmy Buffet and
Paul Simon, introduced by actors Michael Douglas, Julia Roberts and
more.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a Democrat,'' gushed Roberts. ''I've never done anything
political before.''
</P>
<P>
   Although not the biggest names on the bill, Sheryl Crow, Lenny
Kravitz and Jon Bon Jovi brought down the house when they pranced
on the stage and belted out the old Beatles hit ''Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   The event capped a show business day for Gore and Lieberman. The
vice president traded quips with David Letterman in a taping for
his late-night CBS talk show while Lieberman went on Conan
O'Brien's NBC program and crooned a less than tuneful version of
Frank Sinatra's ''My Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson held a news
conference outside Radio City to accuse Gore and Lieberman of
hypocrisy for taking Hollywood's cash while criticizing its values.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pattern is always the same -- cozy up to Hollywood for the
big bucks and then tell the public we're as concerned as the next
guy'' about sexually explicit and violent fare exposed to kids,
Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting Lieberman testified to Congress this week about turning
up the pressure on Hollywood, Nicholson asked, ''What does it say
about a man's credibility when he criticizes them on Wednesday, and
then hobnobs with them and takes their money with a smile on
Thursday?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said Gore has criticized some of his
biggest financial backers while Bush, supported by the oil
industry, for example, has not.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, has had ties to a company that has produced
violent films. Nicholson said that's different because, ''My guy is
not having a fund-raiser here with the powerful elite of
Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Letterman chided Gore for the long kiss he planted on his wife
at the Democratic National Convention. Gore deadpanned, ''To me
that was just a little peck.'''
</P>
<P>
   ''You've been on the road too long,'' Letterman offered.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman even came close to making a prediction as he
introduced Gore.
</P>
<P>
   When Letterman launched a dialogue about environmental problems,
Gore used the occasion to poke fun at his own tendencies to get
overly wrapped up in policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are such a wonk,'' Gore said. ''Are you obsessed with
global warming?''
</P>
<P>
   Playing off a standing feature of the program, Gore also
delivered a Top 10 list of slogans supposedly rejected by his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One was: ''Remember, America, I gave you the Internet and I can
take it away. Think about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
