<HEADLINE> L.A. Transit Talks Near Deadline  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT JABLON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- County officials negotiated with bus and rail
drivers late Thursday as a strike deadline loomed, raising the
prospect of 450,000 people left without a means to get around.
</P>
<P>
   Three unions are involved in the labor dispute with the Los
Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Talks were ongoing as the 12:01 a.m. Friday deadline neared.
However, Goldy Norton, a spokesman for the United Transportation
Union, said there was little progress being made and predicted
there would be a strike.
</P>
<P>
   A top issue had been the MTA's call for a four-day workweek for
some drivers. But the transit agency announced late Thursday that
it had dropped that cost-saving demand.
</P>
<P>
   A strike by drivers, mechanics and clerks would shut down about
200 bus routes and three Metro Rail commuter train and subway
lines.
</P>
<P>
   All sides agreed that a strike would be devastating for nearly a
half-million daily riders. Nearly 68 percent have household incomes
under $15,000 per year and nearly three-quarters are black or
Hispanic, according to the MTA.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there was a bus strike, I don't have money for a cab --
that's $30, $40,'' said Jimmy Jackson, 36, who rides a bus and the
Metro Red Line from south-central Los Angeles to his $300-a-week
job as an auto detailer at a Sherman Oaks Mercedes-Benz dealership.
</P>
<P>
   During a nine-day strike in 1994, county employment dropped by
5,000 jobs, said Jack Kyser of the county Economic Development
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A long strike could affect businesses whose low-paid workers
rely on mass transit, Kyser said, and an upsurge in welfare
applicants could also be possible if the working poor were unable
to get to jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 7 percent of county commuters use buses and trains.
However, the Los Angeles County Federation of Labor, which
represents 800,000 workers, said it would support transit workers.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles unions have had renewed clout in recent years by
organizing low-income workers, said Jaime Regalado, a political
science professor at California State University at Los Angeles,
and director of the Edmund G. ''Pat'' Brown Institute of Public
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Recent victories have included unionizing janitors, home health
care workers and hotel employees.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.mta.net
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
