<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Wraps Up Calif. Tour  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Wrapping up a trip to California, George W.
Bush is marking a day of remembrance for soldiers lost to war in a
city rich with military ties.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will address a rally at a Vietnam veterans memorial on
Friday, National POW/MIA Recognition Day. The setting, in a
predominantly Republican town that's home to a Navy base and many
active and retired military personnel, was among the last stops in
California for Bush, who is struggling to capture the state's 54
electoral votes in November.
</P>
<P>
   Bush plans to return in two weeks and is sending his vice
presidential running mate Dick Cheney to campaign in California
next week.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP presidential nominee blazed through the state's central
region, skirting Los Angeles to visit Orange County, where he burst
into a small-town coffee shop to shake hands with startled patrons,
fielded questions from Hispanic teen-agers at a public high school
and held a rally in an Asian-American neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way he's sought to sell himself as a Republican who
cares about the concerns of minorities, wants to improve schools
and will help working families -- subjects not always associated
with the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Bush running behind Vice President Al Gore among
California voters. At a fund-raiser in San Diego to raise money for
the state GOP, Bush brushed off polls and said he's optimistic
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never been one to worry too much about the conventional
wisdom of the political process,'' Bush said. ''I feel great about
our chances. We are going to carry the state of California.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he ''can't wait'' to debate Gore at three presidential
debates that his campaign finally agreed to. The three prime-time
debates are scheduled for Oct. 3, Oct. 11 and Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know the man is a great debater, but what Americans want is
a leader,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   While in California Bush focused on education reform and
military readiness. He planned to visit an elementary school on
Friday before heading to San Diego's Balboa Park to recognize POW
day.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign said several retired military commanders,
including some nominated to top posts by President Clinton, plan to
endorse Bush.
</P>
<P>
   They include just-retired Persian Gulf commander Gen. Anthony
Zinni; Adm. Jay Johnson, who retired as head of the Navy this
summer; Gen. Ronald R. Fogleman, who resigned as Air Force Chief in
1997; former Air Force chief Gen. Merrill McPeak; and former Marine
Commandant Gen. Carl Mundy, said Mindy Tucker, speaking for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has criticized the Clinton administration for running down
the military and says, if elected, he'll increase soldiers' pay and
spend more on technology and training to improve U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving California Friday, Bush was stopping in New Mexico
before heading home to Texas for the weekend. He was to visit
battleground states in the Midwest and Florida next week, including
a stop in Chicago Tuesday for the Oprah Winfrey Show and one in New
York for the ''Live with Regis'' show on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
