<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists ready to remove mastodon bones from earth  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) - Paleontologists excavating the remains
of a mastodon from a backyard pond will this weekend begin removing
the largest bones.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday the scientists will begin removal of an 8-foot-long,
400-pound tusk from the peat-rich muck where the bones have rested
for the last 12,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   The remains were found last summer when Sheryl and Larry Lozier
dredged and deepened the pond in the backyard of their home.
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologists have since mapped the location of each of the
bones, which is intended to help the scientists investigate the
mastodon - a heavily built elephant-like mammal that became extinct
about 10,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mapping should also provide the scientists with a picture of the
environment at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The excavation is being worked on jointly by the Ithaca-based
Paleontological Research Institution and Cornell University. Since
the discovery volunteers from local colleges have removed many of
the mastodon's smaller bones.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the mastodon's remains will be sent to PRI, where
they will be cleaned, studied and mounted for display. The Loziers,
who own the mastodon, are donating it to PRI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
