<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies 5, Dodgers 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Brian Rose won his third straight decision
and rookie Ben Petrick doubled home two runs Thursday night,
leading the Colorado Rockies over the Los Angeles Dodgers 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Todd Helton was 0-for-4 with a walk, lowering his
major league-leading average to .375. He is 2-for-15 on the
Rockies' road trip and has only seven hits in 35 at-bats against
Los Angeles this season.
</P>
<P>
   Rose (4-2), who didn't get a decision against the Dodgers last
Saturday after being staked to a 6-0 lead, allowed three runs and
six hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Jimenez pitched the ninth for his 21st save in 27 chances.
After allowing runners to reach second and third with one out, he
allowed an RBI groundout to Eric Karros and retiring Mark
Grudzilanek on a grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies left fielder Todd Hollandsworth returned to Dodger
Stadium for the first time since the July 31 trade that sent Tom
Goodwin to Los Angeles and went 2-for-4, singling his first two
times up and scoring on Petrick's fourth-inning double.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Cirillo, who entered with an NL-leading .387 average with
runners in scoring position, capped the Rockies' three-run fourth
with an RBI single for a 3-1 lead against Chan Ho Park (15-10), who
allowed five runs -- four earned -- and nine hits in 5 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Cora, in an 0-for-20 drought, did not move as a breaking
ball from Rose brushed his right kneecap with the bases loaded in
the fourth and forced in the Dodgers' second run.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockies got the run back in the fifth, when Park tried
to pick Jeffrey Hammonds off second and his errant throw deflected
off the glove of Cora and into right-center as Hammonds scored.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers closed to 4-3 in the bottom half on a two-out single
by Shawn Green, who needs four RBIs to reach 100 for the third
straight season
</P>
<P>
   Colorado made it 5-3 in the sixth when Rose singled for his
first major league hit and scored on Neifi Perez's single.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Donnels homered in the second, putting the Dodgers ahead
1-0.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Goodwin went 0-for-4, ending his career-best hitting streak
at 14 games. ... Donnels batted .328 with 27 homers and 84 RBIs in
105 games with Triple-A Albuquerque, and was promoted on Sept. 1
after spending a month on the disabled list because of a sore right
shoulder. ... Dodgers LHP Carlos Perez had arthroscopic surgery
Thursday to have a spur fragment removed from his rotator cuff. He
is expected to be ready for the start of spring training, according
to Dr. Frank Jobe. ... Dodgers C Jim Leyritz had an MRI that showed
a small tear in his right rotator cuff. It prohibits him from
throwing, so he will be limited to pinch hitting. ... Dodgers C
Angel Pena has ligament damage on the outside of the thumb on his
catching hand. He will play through the injury the rest of the
season, but faces possible offseason surgery. ... The Dodgers
committed three errors and have a major league-leading 131.
</P>
</TEXT>
