<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Make Proposals on Digital TV  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Broadcasters may have to deliver more
educational programming and other services to benefit the nation's
children under rules proposed by the Federal Communications
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also took action Thursday requiring that
manufacturers better inform consumers what they can expect from
their new digital TV sets and to resolve thorny copyright
protection issues.
</P>
<P>
   Digital television allows broadcasters to squeeze more video and
data into existing channel space. Broadcasters could use it to
provide sharper pictures or offer additional channels for sports or
movies, or stock quotes and other data transmitted to home
computers.
</P>
<P>
   By 2006, all TV stations must switch to the technology. During
the transition to digital, broadcast stations will air programs on
two channels-- one in digital and the other in the analog format --
so people can still watch broadcast shows on their existing analog
TVs.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC on Thursday laid out how digital TV sets should be
labeled so consumers will know if the sets can connect to cable TV
systems and if they have two-way interactive capabilities. The
Consumer Electronics Association, which represents television
manufacturers, expects the labeled sets on store shelves by the
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also reaffirmed that it will allow cable
operators to require that television makers install special
encryption technology in digital set-top boxes. That is to ensure
that programs in the digital format delivered over cable to
televisions cannot easily be pirated.
</P>
<P>
   ''Program creators expect their digital content over cable
systems to be protected, or they won't make it available,'' said
Robert Sachs, head of the National Cable Television Association.
''Consumers will be the beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Joseph, a spokesman for the Consumer Electronics
Association, said the copyright protection being required by cable
companies could end up limiting the home recording and viewing
rights of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The move to digital television also is prompting the FCC to
re-examine the requirements of broadcasters to serve the needs of
children. The networks now must provide three hours of educational
programming each week, and they are limited in how much advertising
they can show during programs targeted at viewers younger than 13.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is looking at whether the number of hours should
be increased, in light of the fact that broadcasters could offer
additional channels with a digital signal. Because broadcasters
could use their digital frequencies to provide data over the
airwaves, some groups have proposed that schools be given some free
data services.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here's an opportunity for the media industry to really do
something to benefit kids,'' said Kathryn Montgomery, president of
the Center for Media Education.
</P>
<P>
   Following on the heels of a government report that said the
entertainment industry was marketing adult material to youths, the
FCC also said it would consider ways to ensure that promotions
aired during children's shows are appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is considering whether promotions could carry an
electronically coded rating -- as some broadcast television shows do
now -- so that parents could block out objectionable ads with a
V-chip.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcasters now can only air 10 minutes to 12 minutes of
commercials during shows targeted at children, and must follow
other rules to ensure that the separation between ads and programs
is clear to young viewers. But digital television opens the door
for interactive advertising, such as adding Web sites to shows.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: FCC site: http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 0238 </TRAILER>
