<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Sets Up China Trade Vote  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate votes next Tuesday on making normal
trade with China permanent, concluding two weeks of debate and
ending more than a decade of annual battles over trade's role in
stormy U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of that vote is not in doubt -- at least 70 senators
are expected to vote for the legislation that would give American
businesses access to far more open Chinese markets and require
China to abide by international trade standards.
</P>
<P>
   What wasn't clear until Thursday was whether supporters could
stave off a barrage of attempts to amend the bill. Trade backers
insisted it was crucial to keep it amendment-free so it wouldn't
have to go back to the House, which passed it last May, with time
running out in this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Thursday easily defeated six amendments, bringing to
19 the number of amendments voted down over the past two weeks.
Many dealt with China's poor human rights record or the threat of
its exports to American workers, and were offered by senators
contending that this country should not give up trade as a tool in
forcing more responsible behavior from the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   Currently normal trade relations with China must be renewed
annually to comply with a 1974 law on trade with communist states.
But China's upcoming entry into the World Trade Organization
requires the United States to put normal trade on a permanent
basis.
</P>
<P>
   If it does not, U.S. businesses would not benefit from the open
market measures China will effect as part of its joining the WTO
and the billions of dollars in new exports that could result.
Business groups such as the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the
Business Roundtable have made passage of the trade bill their top
legislative priority of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge to an amendment-free bill came Wednesday
when the Senate voted 65-32 to defeat a measure offered by Sens.
Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and Robert Torricelli, R-N.J., on
sanctioning Chinese and other countries trafficking in weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said Thursday that, just one day after that vote,
Chinese officials were again warning the United States of the
''grave consequences'' of building a national missile defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I find it ironic that, on the eve of our new relationship with
China, Beijing is threatening us,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Another note of discord surfaced Thursday when Zeng Jianhui,
chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee of China's National
Peoples Congress said in Washington that Taiwan could enter the
135-nation WTO after China as a ''separate customs territory of
China.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States says that designation for Taiwan is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in a letter this week to Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said there was a common understanding
with China that both China and Taiwan will be invited to accede to
the WTO at the same WTO general council session and that Taiwan
will join as the ''Separate Customs Territory of Taiwan, Penghu,
Kinmen and Matsu.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States will not accept any other outcome,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 0238 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
