<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Friday, as blue chip investors
sought bargains and technology investors took some profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 2.59 to 11,090.06 in the
first hour of trading. The Nasdaq composite index was down 33.35 at
3,880.51, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 4.77 to
1,476.10.
</P>
<P>
   Both moves represented shifts in direction from Thursday's
session, when the Dow index fell sharply on profit-taking and
concerns about the drop in the euro currency, while technology
stocks moved higher on upbeat speculation about corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The markets have lacked a clear direction for weeks, in spite of
the fact that additional interest rates seem unlikely. Instead,
stocks generally move up and down arbitrarily based on a specific
piece of news or economic data.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 5.43 to 533.78.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average was up 0.14 percent. In
afternoon, Germany's DAX index fell 0.19 percent, Britain's FT-SE
100 was down 0.82 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 0.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
