<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell in early trading Friday, as blue
chip investors sought bargains and technology investors gave up
early gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 5.55 to 11,081.92 in the
first hour of trading. The Nasdaq composite index was down 44.56 at
3,869.30, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 4.21 to
1,476.66.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's trading followed a trend that has lasted for several
weeks on Wall Street. The market has lacked a clear direction in
spite of the fact that additional interest rates seem unlikely.
Instead, stocks generally move up and down arbitrarily based on a
specific piece of news or economic data.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported Friday that consumer prices fell in
August for the first time in 14 years, but while the drop was
unexpected, it appeared the market was already beginning to factor
in a slowing in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues were ahead of advancers by a margin of about 7
to 4 on the New York Stock exchange, where volume came to 327.66
million shares, more than double Thursday's pace. Friday was a
triple witching day, when the expiration of stock options and
futures contracts generally cause a spike upward in volume.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 5.10 to 534.11.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average was up 0.14 percent. In
afternoon, Germany's DAX index rose 0.05 percent, Britain's FT-SE
100 was down 0.92 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 0.11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
