<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Seeks Meeting With Iranian  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is
seeking an icebreaking meeting with Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi on the sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly ministerial
debate, U.S. officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Iran are both members of an eight-country
group trying to move the peace process forward in Afghanistan.
Ministers of the so-called ''Six-Plus-Two'' group meet late Friday
at U.N. headquarters, and Albright and Kharrazi both planned to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said Albright was interested in talking
with Kharrazi and had for some time been hoping to establish a
high-level contact. The United States broke diplomatic relations
with Iran after the 1979 hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   An Iranian spokesman, Hossein Nosrat, said Kharrazi planned to
attend the meeting, but declined to say whether the minister
planned to talk with Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been seeking to improve relations with
Iran since the 1997 election of President Mohammad Khatami, a
moderate cleric. Earlier this year, the United States lifted a ban
on U.S. imports of Iranian luxury goods and called for a ''new
relationship'' with the country.
</P>
<P>
   During the U.N. Millennium Summit last week, President Clinton
attended Khatami's speech. Albright was also in the audience when
Khatami addressed a conference on the sidelines of the summit on
the importance of forging a ''dialogue among civilizations.''
</P>
<P>
   A week before the summit, four U.S. lawmakers, including Sen.
Arlen Specter, a Pennsylvania Republican, met with the speaker of
Iran's parliament, or Majlis, Mehdi Karrubi, during a cocktail
reception in New York, the first such meeting of U.S. and Iranian
lawmakers since the Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, hopes were raised that Albright and Kharrazi
would meet at a similar ministerial level meeting of the
''Six-Plus-Two'' group on Afghanistan on the sidelines of the U.N.
General Assembly ministerial debate.
</P>
<P>
   But at the last minute, Kharrazi didn't show up, sending a
deputy in his place.
</P>
<P>
   While Albright and the deputy, Mohammad Javad Zarif, didn't
shake hands or even sit next to each other, it was at the time the
highest-level diplomatic contact between the two governments since
radical followers of the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini seized
the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in 1979 and took 52 Americans hostage.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Six-Plus-Two'' group includes China, Iran, Pakistan,
Russia, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 1159 </TRAILER>
