<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Falls 55; Dow Slips 18  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell Friday, as blue chip investors
sought bargains and technology investors gave up early gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 17.57 to 11,069.90 in
midday trading. The Nasdaq composite index was down 55.01 at
3,858.85, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 7.21 to
1,473.66.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's trading followed a trend that has lasted for several
weeks on Wall Street. The market has lacked a clear direction in
spite of the fact that additional interest rates seem unlikely.
Instead, stocks generally move up and down arbitrarily based on a
specific piece of news or economic data.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported Friday that consumer prices fell in
August for the first time in 14 years, but while the drop was
unexpected, it appeared the market was already beginning to factor
in a slowing in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Software maker Oracle was down $4.13 at $80.81, a day after
investors pushed its price up on upbeat speculation about its
corporate earnings. They weren't disappointed -- earnings beat Wall
Street estimates by 4 cents a share -- but the stock fell Friday on
profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also unloaded shares of Anadigicis, after the wireless
communications company announced its earnings for the last half of
this year would be hurt by reduced orders. Anadigics traded down $5
at $24.88.
</P>
<P>
   On the Big Board, home appliance maker Maytag lost $1.79,
falling to $34.13, after it warned that third and fourth-quarter
earnings will be below Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But shares of Xerox rose $2.25 to $18.25 on published reports
that it is being eyed for acquisition by Hewlett-Packard, Cannon
and others.
</P>
<P>
   ''The month of September is going to be pretty choppy,'' said
John Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at Advest. ''I see
things cooling off and calming down by the middle of next month
because I believe earnings reports overall will be solid, oil
prices should start to drift down and the Fed ... won't raise
interest rates. ''
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a margin of more than
7 to 5 on the New York Stock exchange, where volume came to 638.79
million shares, well ahead of the 580.22 million shares Thursday.
Friday was a triple witching day, when the expiration of stock
options and futures contracts generally cause a spike upward in
volume.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 5.17 to 534.01.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
