<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Still Wants Answer On Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By GEIR MOULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- The United Nations' top human rights official said
Friday she is still seeking a ''credible response'' from Russia to
allegations of widespread human rights abuses in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stand ready to hold senior level discussions'' with the
Russian government on the rights situation, U.N. High Commissioner
for Human Rights Mary Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I continue to be deeply concerned about reports of alleged
serious human rights violations in Chechnya and convinced of the
need for these to be addressed,'' Robinson told an informal session
of the U.N. Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Russia became the first permanent member of the U.N.
Security Council to suffer a formal rebuke from the 53-nation
commission, which criticized Moscow for ''disproportionate and
indiscriminate use of Russian military force, including attacks
against civilians'' in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, put forward by the European Union, urged Moscow
to set up a commission of inquiry and allow in special U.N.
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities -- who snubbed Robinson during a visit to the
region last spring -- denounced the U.N. move and said they wouldn't
be bound by the U.N. resolution on allowing in investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ''My chief concern remains that there be a credible response
from the Russian authorities commensurate with the scale of the
allegations of serious human rights abuses in Chechnya,'' Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has said U.N. rights investigators can
visit the region only as part of their general mandate and not in
connection with the human rights resolution in Chechnya, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were pushed out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war,
which ended with the breakaway region's de facto independence.
</P>
<P>
   The troops rolled back in a year ago, after rebels raided
Dagestan and after apartment bombings in Russia that killed about
300 people. The rebels, seeking independence for Chechnya, have
denied responsibility for the bombings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 1247 </TRAILER>
