<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buffalo teachers return to work  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Striking Buffalo teachers returned to work
without a contract Friday and, to the relief of parents and other
caretakers, promised to stay there until a state mediator issues a
formal proposal early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Union President Philip Rumore said teachers would be in school
through at least Tuesday, when the Public Employment Relations
Board presents the mediator's report.
</P>
<P>
   After working all week, the Buffalo Teachers Federation's 3,700
teachers unexpectedly resumed their strike Thursday morning,
canceling classes for 47,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   The city opened emergency shelters for children, day-care
centers fielded desperate calls from parents, and grandparents were
called into action.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Rosario, 54, spent the afternoon at LaSalle Park
helping watch his 15 grandchildren, 11 of whom normally would be in
school.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh God, no school again,'' Rosario's wife, Bernarda, said when
hearing schools were closed.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden walkout was sharply criticized by Supreme Court
Justice Kevin Dillon who threw out contempt charges against union
leaders on a technicality Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the absolute life of me, I cannot comprehend any reason
whatsoever why someone would conclude that harm from the actions of
this morning would fall on anyone other than the children of the
city of Buffalo,'' Dillon said.
</P>
<P>
   While BTF President Philip Rumore said it was PERB's action that
persuaded teachers to return to class, Buffalo Board of Education
President Paul Buchanan said the judge's admonition was the more
likely incentive.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told them in no uncertain terms... they are not to have any
kind of job action and he called them into court so they could hear
him telling them that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen union executives attended the court hearing
at Dillon's instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said the district's latest offer Wednesday contained no
raise for the 1999-2000 school year, 3.5 percent for the current
year, 2.5 percent for 2001-02, and 2.5 percent for 2002-03. The
union, district officials said, is seeking no raise for 1999-2000,
3.5 percent this school year, 2.75 percent in 2001-02, and 2.75
percent in 2002-03.
</P>
<P>
   The raises would be in addition to 2 percent annual increments
the teachers get regardless of collective bargaining raises,
district officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In court Thursday, Dillon gave the teachers a pass for their
walkout last week, dismissing contempt charges filed against union
leaders. He agreed with BTF lawyers who argued that paperwork
related to a court order forbidding the strike had been improperly
filed.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, however, solidified a temporary restraining order
issued Tuesday ordering teachers back to work. BTF attorney Michael
Sawicki said he expected the city to file new contempt charges
stemming from the latest walkout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
