<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good food, good friends carry diner through 50 years  </HEADLINE>
By JUDY BERNSTEIN
Glens Falls Post-Star
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE GEORGE, N.Y. (AP) - On Wednesday evening, employees of the
Prospect Mountain Diner were at the hospital, visiting a customer
they'd learned was sick.
</P>
<P>
   A regular, he had failed to arrive at his usual time. That
started the worry, longtime waitress Dorothy ''Dottie'' Skellie
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The diner's like a family. Everybody cares about each other.
If somebody doesn't show up, we want to know why,'' Skellie said as
she wiped down a counter on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of family atmosphere that draws workers and
regular customers back to the Adirondack mountain diner.
</P>
<P>
   It its 50 years, as the number of diners nationwide dwindled,
the Prospect Mountain Diner in the small resort town of Lake George
has thrived. It has been featured in Harper's Bazaar and The New
Yorker and was used in an tobacco ad, owner Art Leonhard said.
Famous visitors drawn to the old-time diner include actress
Ann-Margret, Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman and members of the rock
band Aerosmith.
</P>
<P>
   The diner 54 miles north of Albany on state Route 9 - once a
major New York thoroughfare - still sports the original red stools
and booths. On the long Formica counter is a platter of covered
doughnuts. Several small jukeboxes are spaced every couple of seats
and at each booth.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Pat Humphry started working there as a college student
at a vacation job 33 years ago and Skellie started a year later.
Chef Ed Allen started at the diner 25 years ago as a 12-year-old
dishwasher.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is my second home,'' Skellie said, tears welling up in
her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   What attracts people initially can be the diner's look or simply
the promise of solid home-cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The shiny silver diner was built in 1950 in Paterson, N.J., by
the Silk City Dining Car Co. The original owner, Phil Patenaude,
brought the diner to Lake George on two flatbed trucks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, two years after Leonhard bought it, he built an
addition to the back of the diner, where he served Chinese food -
the first in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The full menu includes a dozen kinds of pancakes, as well as
eggs, waffles, hamburgers, sandwiches, soups and pasta. Wednesday's
special includes soups and sandwiches as well as a barbecue chicken
dinner and a sausage, peppers and onions platter.
</P>
<P>
   What draws many people initially is the look, its history and
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Newman, who was visiting from Delaware, said the diner
reminded him of some he'd seen in a museum.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he went in because it served breakfast
mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The food and the friendly atmosphere drew Bob Rostetter, a
frequent customer from nearby Bolton Landing, who's eaten there for
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just one special, it's several,'' he said. ''And no
matter how busy (the waitresses) are, you'll always find someone to
talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sutton of Lake George has come often for more than 30 years
because it's open long hours, which is convenient.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like the atmosphere of it,'' he said. And since he's been a
patron since he was a teen-ager, he said it offers a bit of
nostalgia, too.
</P>
<P>
   Leonhard said the restaurant is ''good food, good service, a
friendly atmosphere and clean.'' He emphasized ''clean.'' It is
not, he said, a ''greasy spoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers include businessmen, construction workers, truckers
and lots of families with kids, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what marks the diner as a landmark as much as anything else
is the change he's seen with those families.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've seen them coming in since they were babies in their
mothers' arms and now they bring in their children,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 1311 </TRAILER>
