<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine, Franks differ in wealth and style  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PLAINFIELD, N.J. (AP) - Bob Franks is the New Jersey
Senate candidate with the political resume, but the election has
become a referendum on political neophyte Jon Corzine - his wealth,
his record-breaking campaign spending, his spotty voting history,
his preference for big-government approaches to health care and
education.
</P>
<P>
   From style to substance, traditional politicking has been turned
on its head in the race to replace retiring Democratic Sen. Frank
Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Franks, a four-term House member, is a consummate
political insider offering himself as the regular-guy candidate.
Multimillionaire Democrat Corzine has never sought office but is
running like an incumbent, largely ignoring Franks and limiting
face-to-face encounters.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, the candidates couldn't be more different
</P>
<P>
   Franks practices aerobic campaigning. During a Labor Day parade,
he jogged to one side of the street, hopped the curb and shook
hands, then jogged to the other side to do the same, all the while
talking without punctuation:
</P>
<P>
   ''Hi folks I'm Bob Franks I'm running for U.S. Senate have a
terrific day!''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, 53, is as understated as his proposals are broad.
Approaching people in public, he asks gently, ''Mind if I say
hello?''
</P>
<P>
   Once the chairman of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., Corzine is worth an
estimated $400 million and spent $36 million just to win the
Democratic primary, mostly his money. Franks has raised less than
$2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But recent polls show almost a dead heat, with 20 to 25 percent
of New Jersey's voters still undecided. While both political
parties want the seat, a Corzine victory is crucial if Democrats
are to overturn the GOP's 54-46 Senate majority.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, 48, is a true organization man, having served two stints
as chairman of New Jersey's Republican Party. His campaign pace is
busy but not frantic. During a break on a day of public events,
Franks nursed an iced tea and a small glass of a New Jersey-brewed
beer at an Irish pub while quietly singing along with Bruce
Springsteen's ''My Hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks fits within New Jersey's tradition of moderate
Republicanism. He focuses on fiscal issues - balancing the budget,
say - but often votes with Democrats on issues like gun control and
federal support for the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Franks seems to have accepted that the campaign is mostly about
his opponent. Halfway through the Labor Day parade, he laughed when
he saw his friend Linda Dashuta waving a bumper sticker popular
among the anti-Corzine crowd: ''Make him spend it all, Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine favors an activist federal government that provides
universal health insurance, nursing-home care, preschool and
college for those with ''B'' averages. Critics say he is too
liberal; Corzine prefers the label ''progressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking the Atlantic City boardwalk on Labor Day weekend,
Corzine told two prospective voters that he'd like to ''spend a
little money on our schools, a little money on our health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Only during a meeting with two dozen congregants at a Baptist
church does Corzine hint at the scale of his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   He says universal health care, which proved too ambitious for
President Clinton, is at ''the top of my agenda,'' and he chides
Vice President Al Gore for advocating too incremental an approach
to helping the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has hurt himself with a series of misstatements. The
most recent was Sept. 6, when he told reporters, emphatically but
incorrectly, that he had voted in a 1998 referendum. The episode
brought renewed press coverage of the fact Corzine did not vote in
17 primary elections and five general elections since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bobfranks.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 1326 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000915.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firm settles discrimination suit with $1 million donation  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Morgan Stanley Dean Witter claimed victory
Friday over a former analyst who claimed the firm discriminated
against him because he is black, saying it settled his lawsuit by
promising a $1 million contribution to the National Urban League.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe this is a complete vindication of Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter,'' the company said in a release announcing the deal to
settle a $1.35 billion lawsuit with Christian Curry. Both sides
dropped their claims.
</P>
<P>
   In the same release, Curry said the episode had been
''emotionally draining ... and to continue would be detrimental to
all.''
</P>
<P>
   ''While I will receive no payment, I am pleased with the
result,'' he said, noting that the National Urban League, a
nonprofit social service and civil rights organization, benefits
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Curry had alleged in a lawsuit - filed in state Supreme Court in
Manhattan and later moved to U.S. District Court - that he was
fired in April 1998 because he is black and because the company
thought he was homosexual after nude photos of him appeared in a
gay men's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The company said in response that Curry, a real estate analyst
who started working for the firm in July 1997, was fired for
expense account abuses.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors looked into the matter and concluded the firm
used poor judgment but broke no laws when it fired Curry. Company
executives had authorized a $10,000 payment to an informant who
told them Curry had paid a computer hacker $200 to plant a phony
e-mail in the firm's computer system.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no discrimination or misconduct against Mr. Curry,''
the company said. ''We were fully prepared for trial and confident
we would win.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm said it would avoid the expense and distraction of a
trial by using money it would have spent on legal costs to make the
donation and ''underscore our strong commitment to furthering
minority interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Benedict P. Morelli, Curry's lawyer, said in the release that
his client can now put the case behind him and move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ''While I initially thought Mr. Curry had a good case, we now
understand that Morgan Stanley Dean Witter engaged in no
discrimination or misconduct against Mr. Curry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morelli did not immediately return a telephone message for
further comment Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
