<HEADLINE> Sunflowers popping up in downtown Winsted  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos
prwatdtfonng
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTED, Conn. (AP) - The seeds of a mystery have been planted
in this Connecticut city.
</P>
<P>
   Giant sunflowers have been popping up all over the downtown.
</P>
<P>
   City hall officials are wondering whether they were the result
of seeds blown in on the winds of a storm, or if, perhaps, the
flowers are the work of a ''Johnny Sunflower Seed.''
</P>
<P>
   Or is someone trying to make a political statement? Winsted is
the home of Ralph Nader, Green Party presidential candidate. The
party's logo is none other than ... a sunflower. Hmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wasn't us,'' said Tom Sevigny, the state Green Party
chairman. ''It wasn't me, let's put it that way. But I think it's
fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind city hall on Main Street about a half-dozen giant
sunflowers have sprouted from the gravel-covered dirt. One plant,
directly next to the rear entrance, is more than 8 feet tall and
yet to blossom.
</P>
<P>
   ''When that flower opens, it's going to be outrageous,'' said
Lee Anne LaClaire, Winsted's social services director. ''I think
there're really something to see. We can't figure out how they got
here but we like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other plants are growing on the U.S. Post Office
property and in front of another building on Main Steet.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers are also popping up on the lawns of nearby homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have about six plants growing in my yard,'' said Eileen
Miller. ''I never planted them, either.''
</P>
<P>
   John Creedon, owner of Connecticut Cut Flower of Bantam, said
the seeds may have originally come from residential bird feeders.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's possible that they could have spread from birds or that
something like a chipmunk buried the seeds to be eaten later on,''
Creedon said. ''But it sounds like someone broadcast the area with
some seeds and may be playing a prank.''
</P>
</TEXT>
