<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crews continue cleanup of oil spill into Sandy Hook Bay  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Wind and high waves from a
storm that blew through Sandy Hook Bay dissipated most of a
30,000-gallon fuel spill that occurred when a tugboat punched a
hole in a Navy ship Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The tugboat Mary L. McAllister collided with the USS Detroit
about 4:20 p.m., ripping a 4-inch-by-4-foot hole on the rear port
side of the 58,000-ton ship. The Detroit, which is staffed by about
500 naval personnel, is designed to accompany aircraft carriers in
battle, restocking them with fuel, ammunition and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened about 700 to 800 yards off the end of the
2.9-mile pier and left a slick 1-3/4 miles long and a half mile
wide.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping channels that were closed immediately after the
accident were reopened Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Protection banned
harvesting of shellfish in Raritan Bay, Sandy Hook Bay, and the
Navesink and Shrewsbury rivers until further notice because of the
spill.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has dissipated to the extent that they're not getting any
measurable quantities of fuel from the skimmers anymore,'' said
Cmdr. Chuck Caudill of the Earle Naval Weapons Station.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not good news for environmentalists, who fear the
toxic effects of the No. 2 diesel fuel on fragile marine life and
shore birds.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's potentially is a very dangerous spill,'' said Andrew
Willner, the baykeeper for New York and New Jersey. ''We have
migratory birds coming here - herons and egrets using the mud flats
- and their fish can become contaminated. Ducks are also landing in
the area and coming in contact with this fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday afternoon, however, there were no reports of any
wildlife dying as a result of the spill.
</P>
<P>
   The spill is one of the largest ever to occur in the bay, said
Cynthia Zipf, executive director of the Clean Ocean Action
environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   She said if the fuel were placed in 1-gallon containers and laid
end to end, the line of containers would reach for nearly five
miles.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a lot of fuel to be in the water,'' Zipf said.
''There's no great time for a spill, but this is a particularly bad
time. Birds are fattening up, getting ready for their migration.
Terns, gulls and kingfishers are going to be exposed to this.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the fall, marine life is so abundant,'' she said. ''All the
juveniles have grown up, and they're feeding voraciously. The whole
food chain is going to get contaminated because plankton is
contaminated, and other marine life feeds off of that.''
</P>
<P>
   A cleanup operation is ongoing. The work is being done by a Navy
response team, a Coast Guard pollution response team and two boats
from private contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy is using a skimmer, a boat that separates the fuel from
the water. One of the contractors used 8,000 feet of boom, and the
other used 5,000 feet to contain the leak.
</P>
<P>
   But the storm that blew through the area at 2 a.m. wrecked much
of the containment booms, which washed up on the rocky bay shore of
Sandy Hook, said Dery W. Bennett, executive director of the
American Littoral Society, a Sandy Hook environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   There was a strong smell of fuel in the air at Sandy Hook Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chances are very little of it was contained,'' Bennett said.
''You can't see a sheen out here, but you can smell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Willner said such a cleanup typically recovers about 15 percent
of the fuel from the water.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports of fuel washing up on any New Jersey
beaches, although some was reported to have reached Midland Beach
on Staten Island, Willner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 1351 </TRAILER>
