<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State's top court hears arguments in Utica mayoral dispute  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Lawyers argued before the state's highest
court Friday whether an exception to a state law governing
succession for city mayors applied to Utica.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals agreed to hear the case after two lower
courts disagreed over whether a special mayoral election should be
held in Utica.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the debate is a state law requiring that the
head of the local legislative body succeed a mayor when the mayor
is unable to complete a full term. The law applies to cities in
which the mayor and the local legislative leader are elected at the
same time for the same term. Utica falls under that category.
</P>
<P>
   On July 3, former Republican Mayor Edward Hanna resigned with
more than three years left in his term. City lawyers, citing the
state law, determined two days later that Common Council President
Timothy Julian could complete the remainder of Hanna's term without
the need for an election. The state Board of Elections concurred
that Julian, a Republican, could keep the job.
</P>
<P>
   But a former county legislator, Edward Revere, said city
residents should choose Hanna's replacement in a special election
this fall. Revere plans to run on the Democratic and Right to Life
ballots if there is a special election.
</P>
<P>
   Revere's attorney, Richard Kaplan, told judges that an exception
allowing city charters to override the state law applies to Utica.
Under that exception, charters dating before Nov. 5, 1975, that
require an election in case of a mayoral vacancy happening before
Sept. 20 supersedes the state law. Revere said Utica's city charter
meets the conditions for the exception and so Julian should be
mayor only on an interim basis.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vacancy (for mayor) occurred prior to Sept. 20, so there
is the need for a vote,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Frye disagreed, saying that the exception originally intended to
affect only New York City and in any event, it may only apply to
cases where there is a vacancy. Since Utica followed the state law
and allowed Julian to succeed Hanna immediately following the
resignation, a vacancy did not exist, Frye reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're trying to say that the exception applies and that the
general rule doesn't,'' Frye said.
</P>
<P>
   In July, state Supreme Court Justice John Tenney ruled that
Julian would have to face Utica voters in November, but a
five-member appeals court panel in Rochester unanimously reversed
that decision. Revere then turned to the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The state's top court, which usually takes months to review a
case, took timing into consideration in this instance and sped up
the process. The court received the request for a hearing in late
August and agreed Thursday to hear arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Judges peppered both Frye and Kaplan with questions throughout
each lawyer's 15-minute presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to say'' what the outcome will be, Kaplan said
following the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Frye said his ''argument went well'' before the six-member
panel.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we'll be successful,'' Frye said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 1352 </TRAILER>
