<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Al Fayed Appeals Crash Verdict  </HEADLINE>
By PIERRE-ANTOINE SOUCHARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- A French court heard an appeal Friday to reopen the
investigation of the car crash that killed Princess Diana and her
boyfriend, Dodi Fayed, along with their driver.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal was launched by Dodi's father, Egyptian tycoon
Mohamed Al Fayed, and the family of driver Henri Paul. The Paris
appeals court said it would announce its ruling Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   A lower court dismissed charges against press photographers who
were chasing the car prior to the Aug. 31, 1997, crash in a Paris
traffic tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Annie Grenier urged the court to uphold the
dismissal, judicial officials said on condition they not be named.
The hearing was closed to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Al Fayed did not attend the hearing. His lawyers argued the
photographers were the principal cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ''Take away the photographers, and there wouldn't have been an
accident,'' Georges Kiejman, one of Al Fayed's attorneys, said
outside the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Judge Herve Stephan threw out charges against
nine photographers and one motorcyclist implicated in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse one-page statement, Stephan ruled that alcohol, drugs
and excessive speed caused the crash that ended the life of the
''people's princess.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The drunken state of the driver prevented him from remaining
in control of the vehicle while traveling at high speed,'' the
judge wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   Tests showed Paul had an alcohol level in his blood of more than
three times the legal limit. He also had prescription drugs,
including the anti-depressant Prozac, in his system.
</P>
<P>
   The photographers had been charged with manslaughter and failing
to assist persons in danger. They acknowledged chasing Diana, the
former wife of Britain's Prince Charles, but rejected any
responsibility in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Stephan found that the photographers' behavior in their pursuit
of Diana, despite its ethical implications, did not ''constitute an
infraction of the criminal code.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodyguard Trevor Rees-Jones survived the crash but suffered
severe facial injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 1428 </TRAILER>
