<DOCNO> APW20000915.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 90; Nasdaq Nasdaq Dips 95  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chips and tech stocks fell sharply Friday
on a mix of profit-taking, bargain hunting and general anxiety
about corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 90.27 to 10,997.20 in
afternoon trading. The Nasdaq composite index was down 95.94 at
3,817.92, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 14.48 at
1,466.39.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported Friday that consumer prices fell in
August for the first time in 14 years. While the drop was
unexpected, it did little to inspire the market, which was already
beginning to factor in a slowing in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Software maker Oracle was down $4.78 at $80.16, a day after
investors pushed its price higher on upbeat speculation about its
corporate earnings. They weren't disappointed -- earnings beat Wall
Street estimates by 4 cents a share -- but the stock fell Friday on
profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also unloaded shares of Anadigics, after the wireless
communications company announced its earnings for the last half of
this year would be hurt by reduced orders. Anadigics traded down
$5.38 at $24.50.
</P>
<P>
   On the Big Board, home appliance maker Maytag lost $2, falling
to $33.81, after it warned that third and fourth-quarter earnings
will be below Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But shares of Xerox rose $1.88 to $17.88 on published reports it
is being eyed for acquisition by Hewlett-Packard, Canon and others.
</P>
<P>
   Another bright spot: Energy stocks, which rallied after
President Clinton expressed concern about oil prices, which have
soared to 10-year highs.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton rose $1.42 to $52.94; Schlumberger was up 98 cents
at $84.75 and Baker Hughes traded $1.25 higher at $38.75.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's downward trading was in line with what has become a
trend on Wall Street. The market has lacked clear direction, in
spite of the fact it appears unlikely that the Federal Reserve will
hike interest rates again. As a result, stocks have moved up and
down arbitrarily, driven by a specific piece of news or economic
data.
</P>
<P>
   ''The month of September is going to be pretty choppy,'' said
John Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at Advest. ''I see
things cooling off and calming down by the middle of next month
because I believe earnings reports overall will be solid, oil
prices should start to drift down and the Fed ... won't raise
interest rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a margin of about
4-to-3 on the New York Stock exchange, where volume came to 833.85
million shares, well ahead of the 685.08 million shares Thursday.
Friday was a triple witching day, when the expiration of stock
options and futures contracts generally cause a spike upward in
volume.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 6.49 to 532.72.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
