<DOCNO> APW20000915.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Ends Conflict with Eritrea  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY DUNPHY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Declaring an end to the war with neighboring
Eritrea, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi said Friday that
negotiations on reaching an overall peace settlement will start
soon.
</P>
<P>
   He also said a cease-fire in the two-year border war between the
two Horn of Africa neighbors agreed on in June was holding even
though no U.N. observers have been deployed to monitor it.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council voted unanimously Friday to authorize
a 4,200-strong peacekeeping force to oversee the agreement and the
removal of troops from the two nations' disputed border.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are now in the second phase of tying up loose ends''
leading to ''a final and comprehensive agreement,'' Meles said. ''I
expect negotiations to resume at the end of the month or early next
month.''
</P>
<P>
   After an agreement is reached, he said, it would take a long
time before normal relations with Eritrea, a former Italian colony
that was once a province of Ethiopia, could be restored.
</P>
<P>
   He praised the United States for being involved in trying to
reach a peace settlement as soon as hostilities broke out
''although we have had our differences particularly with regard to
self defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Former National Security Adviser Anthony Lake was the Clinton
administration's special envoy who helped bring about a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in New York, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright met
separately with Meles and Eritrean President Isaias Afwerki and
said she was encouraged that the two African nations wanted to
reach a settlement as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meles spoke at the National Press Club, while outside
demonstrators from the capital's large Ethiopian community
protested his rule, calling him a dictator. He was here for a round
of meetings with administration officials and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He said his landlocked nation would shop around for use of a Red
Sea port and had 10 possibilities including Eritrea's port of Aseb.
He hinted Ethiopia might seek closer ties with another neighbor,
Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
   ''Economic integration in the Horn is vital for sustainable
development,'' Meles said. ''It might entail political integration
of sorts, but how and when that is achieved we will have to wait
and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The border war with Eritrea left 70,000 persons dead and led to
the displacement of another 800,000.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is backing the U.N. peacekeeping mission but
has said the troops could not be a substitute for a comprehensive
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations plans to dispatch 23 military observers each
to the capitals of both countries in line with a Security Council
resolution authorizing the deployment of up to 100 military
observers. Meles said some of these observers have started arriving
in his capital, Addis Ababa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 1444 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000915.0094 </DOCNO>
