<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, Cuba To Hold Migration Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and Cuba will hold migration
talks next week in New York, the State Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The talks will be Thursday, three weeks after the State
Department protested that President Fidel Castro's government was
preventing Cubans who have U.S. passports from legally leaving the
island. As a result, would-be immigrants had to attempt high-risk
escapes by boat.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Alarcon, president of Cuba's National Assembly and a
Castro confidant, will head the Cuban delegation. William
Brownfield, a deputy secretary of state, will lead the American
side.
</P>
<P>
   Migration talks had been held at roughly six-month intervals,
but none has been convened since December. The State Department has
blamed the Cubans for the long delay.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 28, department officials summoned the chief of the Cuban
diplomatic mission, Fernando Remirez, and handed him a diplomatic
note complaining of Cuban noncompliance with a 1994 agreement
governing migration.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright accused Cuba
of ''increasingly obstructing the safe, legal and orderly migration
of individuals from Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. note said 117 Cubans from 57 families had been denied
exit permits in a recent 75-day period. The United States had
granted all of them visas.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba says a 1966 U.S. law encourages Cubans to undertake
dangerous crossings to south Florida, because it ensures that those
who arrive will not be repatriated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 1512 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000915.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
