<HEADLINE> Auction pulls in big bucks for state historic site  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GREENPORT, N.Y. (AP) - Restoration of Olana, the state's
castle-like historic site, is nearer as a result of one of its
preservationists' most successful auctions.
</P>
<P>
   The auction a week ago raised $40,000 to $45,000 for work on the
1870-1889 Moorish Italianate villa of painter, Frederic E. Church,
an artist of the style known as the Hudson River School.
</P>
<P>
   The group auctioned 103 pieces of art donated to the
organization or sold on consignment for a share of the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just tremendous,'' said Heidi Hill, manager of the
auction and head of the mountaintop historic site overlooking the
Hudson River 30 miles south of Albany. ''It was the second largest
net (profit) generated by the auction in its nine-year history.''
</P>
<P>
   The major piece sold Sept. 9 was ''Resurrection Bay Alaska'' by
Rockwell Kent. It was valued before the auction at $3,000, but sold
for $25,000. Friends of Olana and another Hudson group will split
the profit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's auction raised $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   About $9 million is needed to help renovate the 250-acre estate,
including the mansion's roof and masonry and installation of a new
heating system.
</P>
</TEXT>
