<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani upbeat after undergoing prostate seed implantation  </HEADLINE>
By JUDIE GLAVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had radioactive seeds
implanted in his cancerous prostate gland Friday, and appeared
healthy and relaxed afterward, telling reporters the procedure was
painless and easier than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time that I spent this morning between 8 and 9 was not
nearly as painful as most of my morning meetings,'' the mayor joked
about five hours after the procedure. ''This was actually a much
quieter and more peaceful morning than I usually have as the mayor
of New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at Mount Sinai hospital said the treatment for
Giuliani's prostate cancer went ''perfectly'' and called the mayor'
prognosis ''excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect him to be cured,'' said Dr. Alexander Kirschenbaum,
Giuliani's urological oncologist. ''He's doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Stock said there were ''absolutely no
complications'' during the hour-long procedure, in which he used
tiny needles to insert the 90 titanium metal pellets, each the size
of a grain of rice.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani arrived at Mount Sinai around 6:45 a.m. and was in the
operating room at 7:30 a.m. The mayor, an opera fan, was under
local anesthetic and listened to music by the Three Tenors during
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   He left to return to Gracie Mansion around 2:15 p.m. accompanied
by City Hall aides and his friend, Judith Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a few little pains,'' he said after arriving home.
''Right now I feel pretty good. But I also know it may not be that
way tomorrow, so I'll take it easy today.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted to being nervous before the seeds went in.
</P>
<P>
   ''You go through any form of a surgical procedure, you get a
little tense,'' he said. ''Once it's over, you say to yourself,
'Gee, that was easier than I thought it was going to be.' ... I
went through it with remarkably little pain or discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   The procedure was the second phase of a three-phase treatment
plan. Giuliani has been undergoing hormone therapy for much of the
summer and will later have external radiation treatment, five times
a week for five weeks. He will continue taking hormones for three
more months.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he would probably return to work early next week.
Stock said most patients can resume work immediately after seed
implantation and continue working during external radiation
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds stay radioactive for about two months and can cause
treatable urinary problems, the doctors said, but the side effects
are considerably less than those caused by prostate surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was more candid Friday about his treatment choice than
he has been since announcing in April that he had prostate cancer.
He said he changed his mind frequently about what therapy to have
and made a final decision ''in stages.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I made the decision to take hormones way back four months ago,
and probably made the decision 70 or 80 percent that (seed
treatment) would be the best thing,'' he said. ''I kept my mind
open to other ideas ... and really finally made the decision to do
it this way, 100 percent, about two or three weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Many men Giuliani's age choose surgery to remove the prostate,
but that can cause impotence and incontinence. Kirschenbaum said
seed treatment had an ''excellent'' success rate. The American
Cancer Society puts five-year survival rates following the therapy
above 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mayor took his time, he did his homework,'' Kirschenbaum
said. ''There are so many uncertainties about this disease that you
cannot come out and say this is the best treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, 56, said he felt fine while taking the hormones,
although he experienced some hot flashes and sometimes felt too
tired to work.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was comfortable about dropping out of the Senate race
against Hillary Rodham Clinton, but admitted feeling some regret
Tuesday while watching her debate the man who took his place,
Republican Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''For that one hour during the debate, I was thinking, 'Well, if
I was doing the debate, I would do it this way, I would do it that
way,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, though, he said he couldn't have simultaneously
run a Senate race and undergone cancer treatment. ''My
concentration wasn't there,'' he said. ''My concentration was on
figuring out what's the best cure for cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Giuliani's estranged wife, Donna Hanover, spoke
to reporters after receiving an award for her fund-raising efforts
for breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm doing everything possible under the circumstances to help
him,'' she said. ''I'm also keeping life as normal as possible for
our children, which includes taking them to Atlanta this weekend
for the long-planned wedding of one of Rudy's cousins. We are
grateful for all the prayers that are being said for Rudy's
recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor often appears in public with Nathan, an Upper East
Side divorcee whom he has called a ''very good friend.'' The two
listened to Luciano Pavarotti sing at Madison Square Garden on
Thursday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
