<HEADLINE> Lieberman disavows censorship as means of curbing violent entertainment </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Campaigning for the first time with first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton, vice presidential candidate Joseph
Lieberman said Friday that censoring music would not help to deter
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe in censorship,'' Lieberman told students at
the Mark Twain Intermediate School for the Gifted and Talented. ''I
don't want the government to ever be in a position to tell a music
producer what to put in their product, but I do think that we in
government have a responsibility to be advocates and to appeal to
the entertainment industry to draw some lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and running mate Al Gore this week embraced a recent
Federal Trade Commission report that criticizes the entertainment
industry for marketing inappropriate material to youngsters.
Lieberman has said that he and Gore ''don't want to get into
content'' because that would threaten the First Amendment right to
freedom of speech, but that industry executives should voluntarily
adhere to rules prohibiting the marketing of such products to
children.
</P>
<P>
   When the entertainment industry ''rates products as only good
for adults and then turns around and markets them to kids, I think
we have a right to say, 'Hey, that's not fair. That makes a mockery
of your rating system,''' Lieberman said. ''When you do that, you
make an end-run around parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning with Clinton in her Senate campaign, Lieberman told
teachers, administrators and students that her concern for
improving education was exactly what the country needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore and I really want Hillary Rodham Clinton in the Senate
to help us lead the charge to improve America's public schools,''
Lieberman told the seventh and eighth graders gathered in the
school library.
</P>
<P>
   He detailed the Democrats' 10-year, $16 billion education plan
to recruit 1 million new teachers, which includes raising salaries
and making teachers more accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed with the Gore-Lieberman plan, saying, ''We demand
more and invest more; that's the equation that's especially needed
in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, also tried to bolster Clinton's
support in the Jewish community telling those gathered at the
school that ''Hillary Clinton in the United State Senate will be a
strong, strong supporter of the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Republican Leadership Council, which has spent
about $1 million producing anti-Clinton television ads, said it
would halt such spending if Clinton agreed to sign a pledge by her
Republican opponent, Rick Lazio, to bar soft money from the Senate
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican congressman challenged Clinton to sign the pledge
during the candidates' first debate in Buffalo. The Clinton
campaign has raised millions of dollars so far in unlimited, soft
money donations. The Lazio camp said it stopped accepting soft
money donations in June.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spent Friday touring schools in Suffolk County. He made
appearances in Huntington and Middle Island before ending his day
at the Pulaski Street Elementary School in Riverhead, where he was
greeted with screams and flashbulbs as if he were one of the
Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign has said they won't sign any pact until
Lazio gets signed pledges from at least 14 outside groups,
including the Republican Leadership Council, saying they will halt
the independent ads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 1643 </TRAILER>
