<HEADLINE> French Detain Alleged Basque Leader  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYONNE, France (AP) -- Police on Friday detained an alleged
leader of the Basque separatist group ETA in the southwestern
French town of Bidart, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's Interior Ministry, which also reported the detention,
said Ignacio Gracia Arregui is considered the leader of ETA's
military wing, and allegedly ordered the failed 1995 assassination
attempt of King Juan Carlos of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Gracia Arregui, 45, was taken into custody while he was in
France with his girlfriend, Spain's Interior Ministry said. It said
it carried out the operation in conjunction with Spain's Civil
Guard and the French police.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 800 people have been killed since ETA started its
campaign for Basque independence.
</P>
<P>
   It ended a 14-month truce last December and has since been
blamed for 12 killings, eight of them since June.
</P>
<P>
   ETA, whose name stands for Basque Homeland and Freedom, has
mostly targeted security force members but in recent years has
begun killing members of both the Popular Party and the Socialist
opposition, both of whom oppose Basque independence.
</P>
<P>
   Gracia Arregui has been considered the leader of the military
wing of the ETA since 1992, when the leading members of the armed
group were arrested in Bidart, where he is being held, officials
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
