<HEADLINE> Servicemen's Remains Identified  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The remains of two U.S. Navy aviators
recovered from waters off the coast of Vietnam have been identified
and will be returned to their families for burial, the Pentagon
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One was identified as Lt. Cmdr. Roger B. Innes of Chicago. The
other officer's name is being withheld at the request of his
family.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made on National POW-MIA Recognition Day,
an annual observance by the Pentagon in memory of the thousands of
American veterans who are former prisoners of war and the thousands
who remain missing in action from World War II, the Korean War and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, remains believed to be those of nine U.S.
soldiers missing from the Korean War were flown to Hawaii for
identification. The remains were recovered in North Korea north of
Pyongyang, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The two Navy aviators went missing on Dec. 27, 1967 while flying
an F-4B Phantom jet along the coast of North Vietnam. Communication
with the plane was lost near an enemy target, and a search failed
to locate it.
</P>
<P>
   Based on information received from Vietnamese villagers in 1992
and subsequent interviews with local fishermen, U.S. and Vietnamese
divers in February and March 1998 surveyed an underwater site about
300 yards off the coast. Last year U.S. Navy divers recovered
remains, personal effects of the crew and aircraft debris in waters
approximately 30-45 feet deep. It was the first underwater recovery
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The remains were identified at the U.S. Army Central
Identification Laboratory in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   There are 2,005 U.S. servicemen unaccounted for from the Vietnam
War.
</P>
</TEXT>
