<HEADLINE> Inmates charged with helping murder suspect escape  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) - Four inmates were charged with helping
a murder suspect escape, police said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Xavier L. Valentine, charged with the July shotgun slaying of a
22-year-old Norwich man, slipped out of the Otsego County Jail on
Sept. 1. He stole a minivan from a woman but was spotted by police
and captured a short time later hiding in a barn.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates are charged with cutting the bottom of a fence
around the recreation yard and holding it up to allow the
38-year-old Valentine to slip through.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin A. Garcia, 27, of New York City and James E. Northrop,
24, of Oneonta, were charged with first-degree escape and
first-degree promoting prison contraband, both felonies. Police
said they smuggled a hacksaw blade embedded in a sneaker brought
for one of the inmates by a visitor and cut through the fence over
a two-day span.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph J. McGuire, 21, of Corolla, N.C. and Melvin J. Bliss, 19,
of Oneonta, are accused of lifting the fence. They are charged with
first-degree escape.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is charged with murder, robbery and burglary in the
death of Edward Pastore Jr. Police said he and five others robbed
Pastore of drugs and money before Valentine killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was moved to the Otsego jail from Chenango County
because he had threatened and intimidated other inmates. He was
returned to Chenango County after the escape try.
</P>
</TEXT>
