<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State's top court rules no mayoral election needed in Utica  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - No special election is necessary in Utica to
replace a mayor who resigned with more than three years left in his
term, the state's highest court ruled Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals' decision means that former Common Council
President Timothy Julian can complete the three years left on
ex-Mayor Edward Hanna's term.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, the head of the local legislative body succeeds
a mayor when the mayor is unable to complete a full term. The law
applies to cities like Utica in which the mayor and the local
legislative leader are elected at the same time for the same term,
the court determined.
</P>
<P>
   On July 3, the 78-year-old Hanna resigned because of a heart
condition and his age. City lawyers, citing the state law,
determined two days later that Julian could finish serving the
remainder of Hanna's term without the need for an election. The
state Board of Elections concurred that Julian, like Hanna a
Republican, could keep the job.
</P>
<P>
   But a former county legislator, Edward Revere, said city
residents should choose Hanna's replacement in a special election
this fall. Revere had planned to run on the Democratic and Right to
Life ballots if there was a special election.
</P>
<P>
   Revere's attorney, Richard Kaplan, argued that an exception
allowing city charters to override the state law applies to Utica.
Under that exception, charters dating before Nov. 5, 1975, that
require an election in case of a mayoral vacancy happening before
Sept. 20 supersedes the state law. Revere said Utica's city charter
met the conditions for the exception and so Julian should be mayor
only on an interim basis.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vacancy (for mayor) occurred prior to Sept. 20, so there
is the need for a vote,'' Kaplan told judges at a hearing Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Frye, a private lawyer representing the city, disagreed.
He said the exception originally intended to affect only New York
City and in any event, it may only apply to cases where there is a
vacancy. Since Utica followed the state law and allowed Julian to
succeed Hanna immediately following the resignation, a vacancy did
not exist, Frye reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're trying to say that the exception applies and that the
general rule doesn't,'' Frye said.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals Friday essentially agreed with Frye,
stating that the ''legislative history'' of the state law ''leaves
no doubt as to the limited purpose of the exception.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Legislature did not enact the exception to invite local
departures from the statewide design for mayoral succession,'' the
court said.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals' decision upheld a lower appellate court
ruling. That five-member panel in Rochester had unanimously
overturned an earlier decision by state Supreme Court Justice John
Tenney calling for a special election in November.
</P>
<P>
   Utica Corporate Counsel John Dillon said final decision ''comes
as no great surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very pleased to receive another unanimous decision,''
Dillon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At least it we got a clarification of the law in this case,''
Kaplan said. ''Unfortunately, it seems like no other cities but New
York City can be a part of the (exception).''
</P>
<P>
   The state's top court, which usually takes months to review a
case, took timing into consideration in this instance and sped up
the process. The court received the request for a hearing in late
August and agreed Thursday to hear arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Judges peppered both Frye and Kaplan with questions throughout
each lawyer's 15-minute presentation Friday morning and handed down
the ruling less than five hours later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
