<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pressure continues on Hillary Clinton over money raising  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton is involved in a
''blatant abuse of power'' by having Senate campaign contributors
stay over at the White House or the Camp David presidential
retreat, Republican rival Rick Lazio's campaign manager said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''History is again repeating itself and has reached a new low,''
said Bill Dal Col.
</P>
<P>
   ''The use of the Lincoln Bedroom and Camp David as
accommodations for campaign 'supporters' is nothing less than a
taxpayer-funded abuse of power, and is yet another example of why
New Yorkers can't trust Hillary Clinton,'' Dal Col said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Republican Leadership Council, which has spent
heavily on anti-Clinton television advertising in New York, said
Friday it would halt such efforts if the first lady agreed to sign
Lazio's pledge to bar soft money from the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman had waved the pledge in front of Clinton's face
during their first debate of the campaign Wednesday night in
Buffalo. She refused to sign it and continues to insist that Lazio
get signed pledges from at least 14 outside groups, such as the
RLC, that they will not run such independent ads before she will
sign the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The actions served to continue pressure on the first lady's
campaign over its fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a report in The New York Times on Friday that
President Clinton and his wife met late last week with her
fund-raising team to tell them to step up their efforts. The report
said Mrs. Clinton was ''alarmed'' by the success Lazio has had
raising money.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent filings with the Federal Election Commission
show Lazio had $10.2 million on hand as of the end of August while
the first lady had $7.1 million. That does include the millions of
dollars in soft money she has also raised through other committees.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col said that in addition to releasing the names of recent
overnight guests at the White House and Camp David - something the
White House has agreed to do - the Clinton campaign should ''list
the amount of dollars Mrs. Clinton's guests have contributed to
campaign committees, and to stop this blatant abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the first lady said campaign contributors have been
invited to such sleepovers, but denied any quid-pro-quo involving
invitations in return for money.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have friends and supporters come and spend time with us and
spend the night with us that we are getting to know and who like
spending time with us,'' she said. ''I don't see what's news about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration was criticized after the 1996
re-election campaign for inviting big donors to spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Lincoln Bedroom was never sold,'' Clinton said in 1997,
when aides released a list of 938 guests who had spent the night at
the White House to that point in the Clinton presidency. The list
included political supporters, as well as entertainment luminaries
and old Clinton friends.
</P>
<P>
   In offering to bow out of New York's Senate race, the RLC's
executive director, Mark Miller, said, ''Mrs. Clinton has a
personal credibility problem because she often says one thing and
does another. With our offer today, Mrs. Clinton has the
opportunity to prove she's not a hypocrite.''
</P>
<P>
   The RLC, which includes such Lazio boosters as New York Gov.
George Pataki among its leadership, has already spent about $1
million on anti-Clinton ads.
</P>
<P>
   ''It means one down, 13 to go,'' Clinton campaign spokesman
Howard Wolfson said. ''Now it's time for Mr. Lazio to show real
leadership and get the rest of his allies to sign on the dotted
line and agree to stop their negative campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio camp is convinced Clinton has no intention of giving
up soft money and that the demand for signed non-aggression
statements from so many outside groups is proof of that.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Clinton campaign is addicted to soft money,'' Lazio said
Thursday during a campaign stop in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the RLC move, Lazio campaign spokesman Michael
Marr said, ''The heat just got turned up on Mrs. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Marr said Clinton should also call on the ''various left-wing
outside groups that have already worked on behalf of her campaign
to honor the pact.'' Marr cited the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League and the AFL-CIO as such groups.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL, responding to a letter sent out by Lazio to pro-Clinton
groups, announced Friday that if the congressman could get the
groups supporting him to keep out of the campaign, it would as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has not been raising soft money for his Senate bid, but
has not ruled out doing so if Clinton continues to use it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
