<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Russia Bank in Illegal Deals  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. government has accused a leading
Russian bank of playing a central role in the movement of $7
billion over three years through accounts at the Bank of New York
to fund suspicious or illegal activities worldwide, recently
unsealed court documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Sobinbank said Friday, however, that is has no knowledge of any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, which surfaced in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan in the past week, say ''at the center of this illegal
operation'' were two bank accounts at the Bank of New York for two
Russian banks with common ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts belonged to Sobinbank and Depozitarno Kliringovy
Bank, otherwise known as DKB, and were ''in short, the pipeline for
this illegal scheme,'' according to arguments by federal
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of New York scandal touched off a two-year federal
probe that led to guilty pleas to money-laundering charges by a
former Bank of New York executive and her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Edwards, the bank's former Eastern European Division vice
president, and her husband, Peter Berlin, said they helped Russian
bankers launder billions to avoid Russian taxes and cover up the
money's connection to crimes -- including money used as ransom for a
kidnapping in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government implicated Sobinbank as a key player in the
money laundering scheme as it sought to support its Aug. 20, 1999
seizure of $15.27 million from the Sobinbank account and about
$11,000 from a DKB account.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Conway Casey concluded in an Aug. 25
ruling that prosecutors in the office of U.S. Attorney Mary Jo
White had, at least for now, sufficiently alleged Sobinbank's
knowing involvement in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court cannot fathom how billions of Sobinbank's dollars
could have been transferred out of its constantly replenished (Bank
of New York) account to accounts in the United States without
Sobinbank's knowledge or willful blindness to the scheme,'' the
judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He added that it was early enough in the case that Sobinbank may
still prove at trial that it was an unknowing participant ''either
because the money was not used illegally or because the bank had no
knowledge of its illegal use.''
</P>
<P>
   In footnotes, the judge said he chose to allow the allegations
to be made public because allegations against the bank were already
public and because, despite the bank's claims that it was an
innocent third party to the money laundering, ''there are
allegations in the complaint that suggest Sobinbank may not be
entirely innocent in this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lesch, a lawyer for Sobinbank, said the bank's position
was that it had ''absolutely no knowledge of any wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Serebrennikov, deputy chairman of Sobinbank's board, said
in a statement released Friday that the bank ''is not involved with
the participants'' of the money laundering scandal.
</P>
<P>
   He said the bank is trying to get back money seized,
''principally based on the unproven theory that the seized funds
... were associated with illegal money laundering activities by
persons other than Sobinbank.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Sobinbank has no knowledge of such activities and believes
that the seizure of the funds is illegal and unconstitutional,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted also that the U.S. government has not filed any
complaint or initiated any criminal investigation against
Sobinbank, even though the funds were seized more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Haddad, a spokesman for U.S. prosecutors, declined to
comment Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 1738 </TRAILER>
