<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Criticizes Lee Detention  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nuclear scientist Wen Ho Lee's nine-month
pretrial detention conflicts with America's disdain for ''abusive
executive authority,'' President Clinton said Friday as his
administration came under growing criticism over the handling of
the nuclear security case.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans in Congress called the Justice Department's
pursuit of the Taiwan-born scientist a ''fiasco'' and at least one
Senate hearing on the government's actions has been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old Taiwan-born scientist, fired from his job at the
Los Alamos weapons lab in March 1999 and vilified as a suspected
spy, pleaded guilty to one count of mishandling classified material
and was set free Wednesday. The government dropped 58 other felony
counts that once charged him with endangering some of America's
most sensitive nuclear secrets. He was never charged with espionage
and has maintained he never provided secrets to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers said Friday that Lee had given the go-ahead to
pursue a civil lawsuit accusing the government of violating federal
privacy laws by leaking information suggesting he was a spy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dr. Lee does intend to proceed with his privacy act lawsuit,''
said Heather Hersh, one of his attorneys. The lawsuit, which had
been on hold since May pending outcome of the criminal case, may
also address whether Lee was singled out by investigators because
he is ethnic Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The civil suit, filed shortly after Lee was indicted in
December, is being heard in U.S. District Court in Washington D.C.
Lee's lawyers had argued in the now-concluded criminal case heard
in Albuquerque, N.M., that the scientist had become a suspect
because of his Chinese heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he has seen no evidence of racial profiling in
connection with the Lee case. ''I don't believe that,'' he told
reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But the president, who on Thursday had said he was concerned
about how the Lee matter was handled, was sharply critical Friday
of Lee's pretrial detention -- nine months in solitary confinement,
often shackled and under conditions normally reserved for
terrorists. allowed little contact with even his family.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutor George Stamboulidis said, however, that Lee
spent almost six hours a day, four days a week in the federal
courthouse working with his lawyers on his defense and even
traveled to Los Alamos as part of that effort during his detention.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that the Justice Department, in opposing bail, had
argued strongly that Lee's release on bail would pose a grave
security risk ''and then all of a sudden there was a plea agreement
that was inconsistent with the claims that were made.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That raises a question ... about whether we have been as
careful as we ought to be,'' said Clinton, adding such detention
runs counter to America's traditional opposition to ''abusive
executive authority.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever we hold anybody in prison ... we need to have a very
high threshold,'' said Clinton. ''There ought to be an analysis
over whether that threshold was crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he planned to discuss the matter with Attorney
General Janet Reno, who has defended her department's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Later, White House press secretary Joe Lockhart, when asked the
government owed Lee an apology, said, ''There's no discussion of
that.'' Clinton noted that while most of the felony counts were
dropped, Lee still admitted to having committed ''a serious
national security violation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lee investigation, which caused nearly two years of
controversy and heated exchanges in Congress over the alleged loss
of nuclear secrets to China and lax security at the Energy
Department's nuclear weapons laboratories, will get another airing
on Capitol Hill this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee has tentatively scheduled a
hearing for the week of Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing will address why Lee was kept in solitary
confinement, whether he was a victim of racial profiling, and why
the government abruptly switched from adamantly opposing bail to
letting Lee be set free, said Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   There was ''absolute incompetence'' in the handling of the case,
Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, accused the FBI, and Energy and
Justice departments of ''bungling'' the investigations into nuclear
security problems. ''They need to be held accountable for this
miscarriage of justice,'' Grassley said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
