<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Model refugee camp opens amid joggers and roller-bladers in Central Park </HEADLINE>
By MIRANDA LEITSINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Aid workers and former refugees have built a
model refugee camp amid the joggers, roller-bladers and other
leisure seekers in Central Park to illustrate the experience of the
world's 39 million people who now seek shelter and safety in such
camps.
</P>
<P>
   ''With this exhibit, we hope to spark concern, interest and
knowledge'' about refugees, said Joelle Tanguy, executive director
of Doctors Without Borders, which organized the exhibit. ''We seek
to bring across the scale (of the refugees' plight) and make it
tangible to people.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What would you and your family do if you were uprooted in a
war?'' Tanguy asked at a news conference Friday, the first day of a
two-day exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers from the group, known as MSF from its French name
Medecins Sans Frontieres, led schoolchildren through the camp, from
the three different types of shelters - for tropical, desert and
winter climates - to a water pumping station and food center.
</P>
<P>
   Some children were afraid of the cone-shaped, canvas winter
tents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not sleeping in there,'' said Vaughn Paige, 9, from the
Central Park East 1 School, as an aid worker asked some 10 kids to
lie down head-to-head in a tent.
</P>
<P>
   Other children groaned as they tried to carry buckets of water
about 10 feet. Only one girl was able to carry it a short distance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now imagine if you had to carry that a mile,'' said MSF
volunteer Rondy Anderson, 42, who just returned from a mission in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Davies, a public educator with MSF, said safe water
was one of the most important needs in a camp. ''Cholera is the No.
1 risk in a population displacement. It just spreads like wildfire.
That's why the water source and the waste disposal are so
important.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time MSF, winner of the 1999 Nobel Peace prize,
set up its model refugee camp in the United States. It was created
in 1996 to celebrate the organization's 25th anniversary and has
traveled to several European cities and the United Arab Emirates.
The exhibit will stop at other areas around the city and then
travel to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers gathered at the food center, where they learned that
refugees are usually given two cups of rice, beans, sugar and
vegetable oil for their families. But they were warned that in some
dire cases, only compressed nutrient-enriched biscuits would be
available.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen from Harlem's Thurgood Marshall Academy tasted the
biscuits. Some spat them out, while others said they tasted like a
Ritz cracker.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't like it at all,'' said Angelina Carter, 14.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker Christina Moore, a psychologist who worked with MSF
in Albania during the Kosovo conflict, showed the teen-agers the
makeshift, thatched latrines covered with a blue tarp.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't give you a lot of privacy, does it?'' Moore asked
the teens.
</P>
<P>
   ''What are you going to do to clean yourself?'' asked one teen,
as the others cried out the same question with shock and dismay.
</P>
<P>
   Later, two teens from the group, described to their classmates
the bracelet of life, a paper bracelet with four color-coded zones,
that MSF workers use to see if a child is malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   ''The red zone is the most deadly,'' said Akeem Rasool, 14, as
he held up the arm of a plastic doll at a medical tent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's scary because you have a little child, they are not
healthy and they are going to die,'' said Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the youngsters and educators agreed that the experience
was worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ''It certainly is something that our kids can benefit from. They
need to learn about situations around the world,'' said Shelley
Inniss, 50, who teaches a social change course at Thurgood
Marshall. ''It's important that they compare their lives with
others.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.refugeecamp.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org
</P>
</TEXT>
