<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agency charges GM with harassment, discrimination at Linden plant  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Employees at General Motors Corp.'s Linden
plant passed around pornographic pictures and used racial epithets
while managers did nothing to stop them, the federal government
charged in a discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission sued GM
Thursday on behalf of a black, female employee who said she was
sexually harassed and subjected to a racially hostile work
environment since 1997 at the 2,400-employee plant, which makes
sports utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A male worker in the plant's paint department exposed himself to
employee Mary Scott, and was not punished once Scott complained to
managers, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   At a retirement party in September 1997, employees passed around
photographs of a male manager's buttocks and genitalia, the lawsuit
said. Scott complained in writing and no one was disciplined, the
suit said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott complained on Sept. 18, 1997, that two male employees
frequently used sexually-oriented profanity and made gestures to
simulate sex acts in her presence, the suit said. And the employees
frequently used racial epithets to describe blacks at work, the
suit said.
</P>
<P>
   GM spokeswoman Kelly Cusinato said the Pontiac, Mich., company
had been in discussions with the EEOC and was disappointed by the
lawsuit. The company has completed an investigation of the matter,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She declined to comment on whether employees had been
disciplined, but said the company is ''currently evaluating
appropriate responses to the EEOC complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These are allegations that any employer would be disturbed by,
especially one like General Motors that is committed to creating a
workplace environment that is free from discrimination, hostility
or harassment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, one of two black and female employees among the 16 people
on her shift in the paint department, has been on medical leave to
cope with the stress of her work environment, EEOC officials said.
She filed a complaint with the EEOC in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
