<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Department says official did nothing improper in conversation with Miss America </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - The Labor Department on Friday rejected
allegations that one of its officials tried to improperly persuade
Miss America, Heather French, to change her congressional testimony
in favor of a veterans employment and training bill.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to two House members who bitterly complained about
the alleged conduct of Espiridion (Al) Borrego, Labor Secretary
Alexis M. Herman said ''there were no laws or regulations
violated'' by the official, who is assistant secretary for
Veterans' Employment and Training.
</P>
<P>
   French told The Associated Press in July that on the eve of her
House testimony, Borrego was ''trying to intimidate'' her by saying
that provisions in the bill ''would cause more than 3,000 veterans
to lose their jobs and become homeless. I took that as if he was
definitely trying to shake my testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   While French did not waver in her July 12 testimony, Rep. Jack
Quinn, R-N.Y., demanded an explanation from Herman about Borrego's
telephone conversation with French, and Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill.,
demanded the official's resignation. Quinn is chairman of a House
Veterans Affairs subcommittee and Evans is the full committee's top
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Herman ordered a review by department Solicitor Henry Solano,
and her letters to the lawmakers Friday reported on his
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Quinn, Evans or French could immediately be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Terry Everett, R-Ala., chairman of the House Veterans
Affairs investigations subcommittee, said, ''I am very concerned
about these allegations of intimidation and coercion by an
administration official which appear aimed at influencing the
outcome of VA committee legislation. I, therefore, intend to
request that the Department of Labor's inspector general's office
investigate these allegations. Furthermore, I call upon Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman to look into these charges, and if proven
true, to order his dismissal.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general has considerable independence from
department officials, even though the office is part of the
department.
</P>
<P>
   Herman wrote that the solicitor and the department's career
ethics officer ''concluded that there was no effort to persuade Ms.
French to advocate a particular position in her testimony; modify
her testimony in any way or refrain from testifying.
</P>
<P>
   ''Having reached these conclusions, the solicitor and the ethics
officer determined that there were no laws or regulations violated
by Mr. Borrego or any other member of the staff... .''
</P>
<P>
   French, the daughter of a Marine veteran who was wounded in
Vietnam, has made homeless veterans her cause and testified several
times before Congress about their plight.
</P>
<P>
   Borrego had objected to an early version of the legislation,
which included language that could have cost government-paid
employment counselors their jobs if they didn't meet performance
standards. While the Department of Veterans Affairs runs most
veterans programs, the Labor Department is in charge of federal
employment and training assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Borrego thought that as a matter of courtesy, he should
alert Ms. French that she would be appearing on the same panel as
someone he perceived as a potential critic of the department,''
Herman wrote. ''In retrospect, it appears that not enough planning
went into this call and Mr. Borrego became overly detailed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Borrego has advised me that he regrets that Ms. French
initially interpreted the call in a different way, and that it was
not his intent to affect her testimony in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Borrego issued his own statement, saying he ''regrets any
confusion stemming from my telephone conversation with Ms. French''
and said he looked forward to working with her on behalf of
veterans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 1802 </TRAILER>
