<HEADLINE> BIC responds to national lighter recall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MILFORD, Conn. (AP) - A New Jersey company is recalling about
294,000 disposable cigarette lighters made by Milford-based BIC
Corporation because they lack federally required child-resistant
mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   Vaid Enterprises of Jersey City, N.J., is recalling the lighters
because young children could ignite them, the Consumer Product
Safety Commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the company nor the agency is aware of any injuries
involving the lighters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The recalled lighters are gray goods, meaning they were never
intended for sale in the U.S., and were illegally brought into this
country by Vaid Enterprises,'' said Thomas M. Kelleher, senior vice
president-administration and general counsel for BIC. ''The
recalled lighters were produced in a BIC factory in France for sale
in markets outside the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The disposable lighters being recalled are oval-shaped ''BIC''
and mini-''BIC'' brand lighters. They have a green, red, blue,
black or yellow body and a metal top.
</P>
<P>
   The standard size lighters have the UPC number 3 086120 600020.
The mini-lighters have the UPC number 3 086120 600051.
</P>
<P>
   Convenience, gas, grocery and thrift stores in the East sold the
lighters from January through April for about $1 each.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should stop using these lighters immediately and
return them to the place of purchase for a refund.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, consumers should call the CPSC at
1-800-638-2772.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Product Safety Commission: http://www.cpsc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
