<HEADLINE> Reform Party takes its fight to state Supreme Court  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW DALY
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD - The fractious Connecticut Reform Party has taken its
fight over the presidential ballot to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Francis McDonald Jr. will preside Monday, as
lawyers for the party's two competing factions argue whether Pat
Buchanan or John Hagelin deserves the Reform line on the state
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The high-court hearing was scheduled after Buchanan's supporters
filed a lawsuit in Hartford Superior Court to get Buchanan's name
on the ballot. They claim the conservative commentator deserves the
Reform line because he was chosen at their raucous nominating
convention in Long Beach, Calif. last month.
</P>
<P>
   But Hagelin's backers, who walked out of that convention and
held their own across the street, call the pro-Buchanan vote
invalid. They say Hagelin, an Iowa physicist, is the party's real
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The squabble has led state elections officials to declare the
party ''over-nominated.'' Until the internal differences are sorted
out, neither man will be listed on the Reform Party line of the
ballot, Secretary of the State Susan Bysiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is already on the ballot in Connecticut as the
candidate of the Freedom Party. But his supporters, unhappy with
Bysiewicz's decision, filed suit this week to place Buchanan's name
on the Reform line as well.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before a scheduled hearing on the case Friday, Buchanan
supporters agreed to move the claim from the Superior Court to the
Supreme Court, after Hagelin's supporters had threatened to seek an
injunction on jurisdictional grounds.
</P>
<P>
   John Conway, a lawyer representing the pro-Buchanan faction,
said he was pleased McDonald had agreed to hear the case so
quickly. He expects a ruling by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm confident we'll prevail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conway and other Buchanan supporters cited a ruling this week by
the Federal Election Commission awarding Buchanan $12.6 million in
federal campaign funds belonging to the Reform Party. In a related
development, a California judge ruled Wednesday that Buchanan, not
Hagelin, is the Reform nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Donovan, state chairwoman of the Reform Party and a
Hagelin backer, said she also is pleased the case will be decided
by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Reform party members in the state do not share
Buchanan's ideology, Donovan said, and should not be saddled with
him as the party's presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have a strong case,'' Donovan said. ''This is
precedent-setting in terms of the rights of a state party
organization to be in charge of their own destiny.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 1812 </TRAILER>
