<HEADLINE> Storm Drenches Yucatan Peninsula  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A powerful storm drenched the Yucatan
Peninsula on Friday and moved into the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters at the National Hurricane Center in Miami said the
storm could possibly menace the Gulf coast from Texas to Florida in
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   No deaths or injuries were reported as the storm, packing winds
of 35 mph, roared across the Yucatan Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Flood waters rose to knee-level in low-lying areas of the resort
city of Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's National Weather Service said the storm is expected to
bring heavy rain to five Mexican states.
</P>
<P>
   Moving northwest at about 6 mph, the storm could be in the
middle of the Gulf and near hurricane strength by Monday,
forecasters said. Storms become hurricanes if the winds hit 74 mph.
</P>
