<HEADLINE> Judge rules evidence was improper in detective's drug case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) - Police improperly seized pharmacy
records in the case of a Hartford police detective accused of using
fake prescriptions, a judge ruled Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Russo should have had a reasonable expectation of
privacy about his prescription records, Superior Court Judge Stuart
Schimelman found.
</P>
<P>
   Russo's defense argued the pharmacy records were obtained
improperly, without search warrants or subpoenas. Russo was charged
with fraudulently obtaining controlled substances and forgery.
</P>
<P>
   After the ruling, State's Attorney Kevin Kane moved to dismiss
the charges but got permission from the judge to bring the case
before the state Appellate Court.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on that decision, the state had insufficient evidence to
go forward,'' Kane said in an interview after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Kane has 20 days to decide whether to appeal. If the Appellate
Court sides with Schimelman, the charges against Russo will be
dismissed. If the court decides Schimelman erred, the criminal case
against Russo may continue.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors wanted to use the records to show that Russo used
fake prescriptions to obtain between 15,000 and 18,000 tablets of
Tylenol 3 with codeine from four pharmacies between January 1996
and October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Russo has been suspended from the police force. He has filed a
federal civil lawsuit against the city and Hartford police leaders,
accusing them of violating his civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims their actions were part of a pattern of
harassment by the Hartford department. Russo said he was singled
out because he had worked with federal agents who identified the
correct suspect in a shooting after Hartford police arrested the
wrong man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 1838 </TRAILER>
