<DOCNO> APW20000915.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suffolk Executive releases his 2001 budget plan  </HEADLINE>
By PAT MILTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) - Suffolk County Executive Robert Gaffney
on Friday released his $1.98 billion budget proposal for 2001,
which calls for a tax increase of about $82 a year for residents of
Suffolk's five western towns.
</P>
<P>
   Households in Suffolk's eastern towns which do not come under
the county police department would have a tax hike of about three
dollars a year under the new budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one is ever pleased at the prospect of raising taxes, even
slightly,'' Gaffney said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the tax hike was due largely to a $35 million increase
in the police district taxes as a result of a binding arbitration
decision. Rising medicaid and health insurance costs were also
factors in the tax increase, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tax bill for residents in the five western towns,
Huntington, Babylon, Smithtown, Islip and Brookhaven, would
increase by an average of $6.89 a month, or just over $82 a year.
Residents in the eastern towns of East Hampton, Southampton,
Shelter Island, Southold and Riverhead would pay around three
dollars a year more.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.98 billion budget is 6.6 percent increase over last year.
It will be sent to the Suffolk County Legislature, which will hold
public hearings on the budget plan and make its recommendations. A
budget must be approved by Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Gaffney said Suffolk County is in excellent economic health. He
projected a $77 million surplus this year, and noted that Standard
and Poors upgraded the county's bond rating from BBB+ to A as of
last May.
</P>
<P>
   ''Suffolk County continues to benefit from both a strong economy
and a dynamic and diversified economic base,'' said Gaffney. ''It
has been a period of unparalleled economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Nassau County, county officials are trying to ward
off the takeover by a state financial control board. County
Executive Thomas Gulotta and his staff were putting the last
touches on a proposed budget for 2001 and a financial plan for each
of the next four years to reduce the county's deficit. The budget
plans had to be presented to the county legislature and the Nassau
Interim Finance Authority by Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta has released portions of his plan to close the county's
$143 million budget gap, which include layoffs of 350 workers,
early retirement and attrition of another 300 jobs, a property tax
increase, and a tax on entertainment tickets sold at the Nassau
County Veterans Memorial Coliseum and Westbury Music Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta's plan has been met with pessimism by some members of
the county legislature who question whether his steps for reducing
the deficit will be sufficient to convince state NIFA officials
that the county can get back on a strong financial footing without
a fiscal takeover.
</P>
</TEXT>
