<HEADLINE> Lazio misspeaks on voting age during visit to elementary school  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) - U.S. Senate candidate Rick Lazio was so
overwhelmed by the enthusiastic greeting he received Friday at the
Pulaski Street Elementary School that he told the students he
wished they were old enough to vote - only he got the voting age
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''Boy, I wish all of you were 21 years old right now,'' the
Republican congressman said after being welcomed into a school
auditorium by shrieks of approval and applause usually reserved for
the likes of The Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   The error was quickly seized upon by the state's Democratic
organization, which fired off a press release suggesting Lazio was
proposing to repeal the 26th amendment, which gave the right to
vote to 18-year-olds in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ''According to the latest census data, there are 731,898 New
Yorkers aged 18-20. Apparently Rick Lazio is not interested in
getting their vote,'' said Peter Kauffmann, spokesman for the New
York State Democratic Party. ''I'd like to invite all New Yorkers
aged 18-20 to register and vote - there is room for you in the
Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spokesman Michael Marr declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
