<HEADLINE> Thoughts from 2 miles up: A reporter's first dive  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOVE WILLIAMSTOWN, N.J. (AP) - I wasn't scared until we were at
the open plane door - looking 13,000 feet down. But then it was too
late to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   I had seen what happened to the other people who had just left
the plane. They got snapped away and started falling - fast.
</P>
<P>
   But when my skydiving instructor stepped out, I didn't have any
choice but to go with him, we were harnessed together.
</P>
<P>
   We shot down and were ripped away from the plane. Too scared to
speak, or do anything else, I just watched the clouds zoom by.
</P>
<P>
   For 60 long seconds, instructor Mark Kruse and I fell together,
the wind snapping in our ears. The air, surprisingly cold for a hot
September day, rushed past.
</P>
<P>
   A skydiver with a video camera attached to his head dove with us
to capture my first dive. At one point, he grabbed my hand in a
handshake and spun me around in a gut-wrenching circle. Things seem
to happen faster up here.
</P>
<P>
   I repeated to myself what Kruse had told me before we got on the
plane, ''Just arch your back, breathe and relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skeffington, manager of Freefall Adventures, had given me
about 20 minutes of instruction on the ground on how to position my
arms and how to land, but he and Kruse acknowledged that most
people forget all that when they get up in the air. ''Arch, breathe
and relax,'' I could handle.
</P>
<P>
   The other thing I had to remember - this one rather crucial -
was when to pull the ripcord. Kruse, of course, had his own cord,
but students are supposed to get the feel of pulling their own.
</P>
<P>
   When we reached 5,000 feet, I was to pull the orange handle at
my hip and release the parachute. I checked the altimeter strapped
to my wrist several times, surprised that we weren't there yet.
While I was enjoying the amazing ride, I knew I'd relax a little
once the chute opened.
</P>
<P>
   At just before 5,000 feet, Kruse gave me the OK and I pulled the
cord. The red, white and blue parachute opened with a snap, yanked
us up with surprising force, then settled us into a smooth float.
</P>
<P>
   Kruse gave me a thumbs up, I took a deep breath and enjoyed the
ride - calm, peaceful and beautiful. For five minutes, homes,
trees, baseball fields and golf courses drifted by. Philadelphia,
about 20 miles away, looked like a small town in the distance, and
clouds hugged the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting it to be over and at the same time not wanting it to
end, I reminded myself that this is probably the only time I'll
ever do this. So I tried to soak it all up - the graceful, floating
feeling, the beauty, the serenity.
</P>
<P>
   When we reached 1,000 feet, Kruse let me help steer the rig
toward the landing zone - a gravel 'X' in the middle of a field. We
angled in toward the ground and landed smoothly, but still a
surprising jolt ran up my legs.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved and excited, I felt like I'd accomplished something,
even though all I did was hang on for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after landing my stomach is still queasy and my legs are
shaking. I'm afraid to eat anything because I can't be sure it'll
stay where it's supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, nothing is the same. The sky seems bluer, the
clouds brighter white, the day happier. It's not just relief that
nothing went wrong. It's an intangible - the joy of having taken
that first step out and the peace of being in one piece 13,000 feet
later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
