<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Votes To Honor Slaves  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate completed congressional action
Friday on an effort to honor slaves whose forced labor helped build
the U.S. Capitol, the seat of American democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved by voice vote a measure to authorize the
speaker of the House and the president pro tem of the Senate to set
up a special task force to study the history and contributions of
slave laborers toward building the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The task force then is to recommend a memorial to be displayed
on the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed its version Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''These men, these slaves, laid the very foundation of our
democracy,'' said Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill was sponsored by Sens. Spence Abraham, R-Mich.,
and Blanche Lincoln, D-Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional historians say slaves did much of the 18th- and
19th-century work constructing the building.
</P>
<P>
   Slaves were the largest locally available labor pool in 1790
when Congress ordered a new capital to be carved out of two
slave-owning states, Virginia and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   When the three commissioners in charge of construction began
building in 1792, they hired field hands from local small farmers
and planters. Local slaves were available to be rented from their
owners cheaply, an average of $55 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Many white laborers worked under similar conditions as the
slaves, but their employment was voluntary, and they could keep the
money they earned.
</P>
<P>
   Local historian Bob Arnebeck, in his 1991 book, ''Through a
Fiery Trial, Building Washington, 1790-1800,'' wrote that as work
began, slaves served as axmen, cutting trees on Jenkins Hill on
which the new Capitol would stand.
</P>
<P>
   Some helped square logs needed for construction. Others cleared
trees and stumps from the new streets laid out by city planner
Pierre L'Enfant.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The bills, S. Con. Res. 130 and H. Con. Res. 368:
http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
