<HEADLINE> Justice Dep't Sues Over Tomatoes  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department filed a civil antitrust
suit Friday that it said was designed to offer consumers a better
choice of vine-ripened tomatoes in winter.
</P>
<P>
   The department's antitrust division sued in U.S. District Court
in Tucson, Ariz., to overturn a private agreement that it said
reduced competition in the development of seeds for long-shelf-life
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Long-shelf-life tomatoes, now generally grown in Mexico, can
ripen on the vine and be shipped year-round to distant locales for
sale before spoiling. Now, a majority of the fresh tomatoes sold in
stores in the United States during winter are picked in southern
climates while still green and then gassed until they redden.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. consumers spend $4 billion a year on fresh tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed against LSL Biotechnologies Inc., Seminis
Vegetable Seeds Inc., and their joint venture, LSL Plant Science.
It seeks to void an agreement that prohibits a competitor, Hazera
Quality Seeds Inc. from developing and selling seeds for
long-shelf-life tomatoes in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The department said LSL and Hazera entered a contract to develop
seeds for such tomatoes. The contract has expired except for a
provision that bars Hazera from developing the seeds that allow
farmers to get vine-ripened tomatoes long distances to market in
winter before they spoil.
</P>
<P>
   ''Competition to innovate spurs companies to offer consumers
more choices and higher quality products at better prices,'' said
Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein. ''This agreement deprives
American farmers and consumers of the full benefits of that
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   LSL Biotechnologies' attorney was not immediately available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   LSL and Seminis are the dominant sellers of seeds used to grow
fresh tomatoes in North America during winter. The government said
Hazera, one of the largest producers of seeds in Europe and the
Middle East, is one of only a few companies with the interest and
expertise to develop and market new long-shelf-life tomato seeds to
American farmers in competition with the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   LSL Biotechnologies and LSL Plant Science are headquartered in
Tucson, Ariz. Seminis is the largest developer, producer, and
marketer of vegetable seeds in the world. It is headquartered in
Saticoy, Calif., and is a majority-owned subsidiary of Savia, a
Mexico-based conglomerate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 1855 </TRAILER>
