<HEADLINE> Ford to reopen truck plants shutdown for tire recall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) - Ford Motor Co. said Friday it would reopen three
truck factories that had been closed three weeks so tires meant for
new vehicles could be used as replacements in the recall of 6.5
million Firestones.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown of plants in St. Paul, Minn., Edison, N.J. and
Hazelwood, Mo., diverted about 100,000 tires to the recall, Ford
spokeswoman Della DiPietro said. She said Ford decided to reopen
the plants because the tire industry was producing 50,000 more
P235/75R15-size tires each week than when the shutdown began.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said Thursday about 2 million of the 6.5 million recalled
tires had been replaced. The Firestone tires under recall have been
linked to at least 88 deaths and 250 injuries by federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   During the shutdown, Ford lost production of 15,000 Ford
Explorers/Mercury Mountaineers and 23,500 Ford Ranger pickups, not
all of which would have used the 15-inch tires under recall. Some
tires also came from Ford switching some production from 15-inch to
16-inch tires.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro said Ford would make up the lost Ranger production, but
would not make up the Explorer/Mountaineer production. The shutdown
will not delay the launch of the 2002 Explorer/Mountaineers early
next year, but will push back some retooling.
</P>
<P>
   The plants employ about 6,000 workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
