<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Attends Afghanistan Meeting  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi attended a closed-door
meeting Friday on Afghanistan, an encounter which U.S. officials
hope will be an ''ice breaker'' in U.S.-Iranian relations.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Iran are members of an eight-country group
that has been working to end the long civil war in the central
Asian nation and advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Kharrazi arrived first, and Albright followed. Neither spoke to
reporters. In the conference room, they sat down on opposite sides
of a horseshoe-shaped table. The doors then shut.
</P>
<P>
   The ministerial session of the group on Afghanistan was held on
the sidelines of the annual U.N. General Assembly debate and was
attended by Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said Albright was interested in talking
with Kharrazi and had for some time been hoping to establish a
high-level contact. The United States broke diplomatic relations
with Iran after the 1979 hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   An Iranian spokesman, Hossein Nosrat, declined to say whether
Kharrazi planned to talk with Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, hopes were raised that Albright and Kharrazi
would meet at a similar meeting of the ''Six-Plus-Two'' group on
Afghanistan. But at the last minute, Kharrazi didn't show up,
sending a deputy in his place.
</P>
<P>
   While Albright and the deputy, Mohammad Javad Zarif, didn't
shake hands or even sit next to each other, it was at that time the
highest-level diplomatic contact between the two governments since
radical followers of the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini seized
the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 Americans hostage.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the General Assembly on Friday, Kharrazi called
for international efforts to combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a globalized world, nothing can justify harboring or
providing safe havens to terrorists or condoning their
activities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States accuses Iran of sponsoring terrorism but has
been seeking to improve relations with Iran since the 1997 election
of President Mohammad Khatami, a moderate cleric who has pushed
democratic reforms in the face of hard-line opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the United States lifted a ban on U.S.
imports of Iranian luxury goods and called for a ''new
relationship'' with the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Khatami said in New York last week that ''serious issues''
must be resolved between the two countries before there can be
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   During the U.N. Millennium Summit last week, President Clinton
attended Khatami's speech. Albright was also in the audience when
Khatami addressed a conference on the importance of forging a
''dialogue among civilizations.''
</P>
<P>
   A week before the summit, four U.S. lawmakers, including Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., met with the speaker of Iran's parliament,
Mehdi Karrubi, at a cocktail reception in New York, the first such
meeting of U.S. and Iranian lawmakers since the Islamic revolution
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Friday, Kharrazi said Iran backed a broad-based
and representative government for Afghanistan, which is largely
controlled by the Taliban Islamic militia.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, who are mostly Sunni Muslims, accuse Iran, an
overwhelmingly Shiite Muslim nation, as well as Russia and other
central Asian states of aiding their northern-based enemies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
