<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Addresses Welfare Reform  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The highly praised reductions in the nation's
welfare rolls might have occurred as much because of the nation's
booming economy as the 1996 welfare law, panelists at a
Congressional Black Caucus hearing said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is premature to call welfare reform a success,'' said
William Julius Wilson, a social policy professor at Harvard
University. ''We have no idea what will happen to these families
when the economy returns to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton celebrated the success of the 1996 welfare
reform law last month on its fourth anniversary. Welfare rolls are
half what they were four years ago, he said, and the percentage of
Americans on welfare is at its lowest level in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's panel on the success of welfare reform law, chaired by
Rep. Danny Davis, R-Ill., as part of the caucus' annual legislative
conference, said the real test of the law will come when the
economy stabilizes or drops. ''Many of the conclusions that have
been reached are premature,'' said Ron Walters, a professor of the
University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's Wilson said poor single mothers fare the worst under
the new law. And, he said, ''If they're struggling now, what will
happen to these women when the economy slows down or returns to
normal?''
</P>
<P>
   Congress probably will return to the law next year. When it
does, one expected suggestion is that Congress give more help to
workers in transportation and child care.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 welfare law encouraged recipients to enter the work
force by limiting the time they can collect benefits and requiring
them to work while drawing welfare. It also offered incentives to
employers to hire welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people leaving welfare who want to work have no way to
get from their homes to where the jobs are, said Gary Jefferson,
vice president of United Airlines. ''Unless you solve the problem
of transportation, there's no point in wondering where the
welfare-to-work program goes from here,'' Jefferson said.
</P>
<P>
   There's also discrimination against minorities who have been
unable to get off welfare, panelists said, and a perception remains
among businesspeople that people on welfare don't want to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they perceive those people are ... people who aren't going
to help their businesses, they won't hire them,'' said Rodney
Carroll, chief operating officer of the Welfare To Work Project.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will speak to the caucus Saturday night. ''I think the
president will use this opportunity to talk about all that we've
accomplished over the last 7&AMP;frac12; years with his allies within the
(caucus),'' spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
