<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Could Save Caribbean Murders  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW J. ROSENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) -- A ruling by Britain's Privy Council
that could save hundreds of convicted murderers from execution on
Caribbean islands has prompted some politicians to reconsider ties
to British law.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether or not the death penalty should continue is not for
others to determine,'' said Jamaica's Prime Minister P. J.
Patterson, who is among several Caribbean leaders eager to resume
hangings amid rising crime, much related to drug-trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said the ruling was ''another compelling reason'' to
create a Caribbean court to replace the Privy Council, which is
drawn from members of Britain's House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke Wednesday night, the day after the council commuted the
death sentences of six Jamaicans to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-1 ruling does not stop Caribbean governments from
executing convicted murderers, but experts say it places new, and
possibly insurmountable, obstacles in their way. And at least one
human rights activist cautiously claimed victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''This affects every death row prisoner in every country under
the jurisdiction of the Privy Council,'' said Jamaican human rights
attorney Hilaire Sobers. ''The cases of those who already had been
condemned will now have to be revisited.''
</P>
<P>
   The council -- the final court of appeal for nine independent
former colonies in the Caribbean and five British territories --
ruled that inmates should be allowed lawyers when appealing before
Jamaica's Privy Council, which advises on mercy pleas, and said
that should apply throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   The Privy Council also objected to a Jamaican law allowing
death-row prisoners only six months to have appeals heard by
international human rights commissions. And it reaffirmed an
earlier decision mandating that no more than five years can elapse
between sentencing and execution, judging any further delay cruel
and inhumane punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Those favoring hanging said the ruling will provide the needed
impetus for the region to establish its own appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ruling marks the beginning of the end of executions in
Trinidad and Tobago and indeed the Caribbean,'' said Israel Kahn, a
pro-death penalty attorney in Trinidad, which last year resumed
executions after a five-year hiatus, hanging 10 people including an
alleged drug lord and eight gang members.
</P>
<P>
   In Jamaica, a country of 2.6 million people, no executions have
taken place since 1988. But public pressure to resume hangings is
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency that pro-death penalty politicians and activists
have placed on establishing the regional court has led human rights
activists to dub the new body ''the hanging court.''
</P>
<P>
   But Patterson claimed the issue was about national sovereignty,
not just executions.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International said Trinidad is using sovereignty to
defend human rights violations, including executions.
</P>
<P>
   English-speaking Caribbean nations, with a population of 5
million, have about 250 people on death row -- more than 100 in
Trinidad alone -- one of the highest death sentence rates in the
world, Amnesty International has said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 1955 </TRAILER>
