<DOCNO> APW20000915.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> County drops prison contractor with link to corrupt officials  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KINGSTON, N.Y. (AP) - A construction firm that paid $10,000 to a
water commissioner later linked to government corruption has been
dropped as the contract for a new, $53 million jail.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster County decided Thursday not to sign a $2.5 million
contract with Barry, Bette and Led Duke, an Albany-based
construction company, because of the company's ties to Fred Andros.
</P>
<P>
   During the investigation of a Dutchess County extortion case, it
was discovered that BBL paid $10,000 to Andros, then-Poughkeepsie
water commissioner, in return for necessary permits.
</P>
<P>
   Andros was an associate of William Paroli Sr., the former
Dutchess County Republican chairman who admitted in February that
he conspired to extort payments from companies doing business in
the Town of Poughkeepsie.
</P>
<P>
   Paroli got 21 months in jail; Andros was sentenced to 33 months
for conspiracy and awaits trial on charges he murdered the town's
personnel director.
</P>
<P>
   BBL says it was a victim of extortion. It never faced any
charges.
</P>
<P>
   But the connection to Paroli and Andros was enough, county
officials said, insisting their decision was not a reflection on
BBL's ability.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our decision reflects only the desire of the county to have
this extremely important project proceed without the distractions
and questions that have arisen because of the firm's past
activities,'' said Ward Todd, majority leader of the county
legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
