<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Desperate For Mideast Deal  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Clinton administration, in a desperate
stretch run for a Mideast peace accord, is looking to Arab leaders
to ease Yasser Arafat into a compromise over the Holy City of
Jerusalem. The strategy appears not to be succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia's Crown Prince Abdullah has publicly ruled out
compromise. ''There is nothing to negotiate about and compromise on
when it comes to Jerusalem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was having dinner Friday
night with Abdullah as U.S. diplomatic efforts to mediate peace
terms with Israel and the Palestinians appeared at a crossroad.
</P>
<P>
   In his standoff with Israel on the future of Jerusalem, Arafat
carries the flag not only for the Palestinians but for the Arabs at
large. Their objections to Israel's 33-year control of all of
Jerusalem have not been appeased by the freedom all faiths have had
to worship.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat casts his demand for Palestinian sovereignty over East
Jerusalem in terms of a Muslim liberation movement. In this vein,
he has rejected proposals by President Clinton and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak that would give the Arabs control of sacred
mosques but deny sovereignty over East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, preparing for the stretch run, Albright sent Edward
Walker, a U.S. diplomat with wide experience in the Middle East, on
a long trip to Arab capitals.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to convince Arab leaders that the Jerusalem problem can
be resolved only by compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Several governments made statements indicating they have no
intention of coaxing Arafat into compromise, but U.S. officials
said their private message was that settlement had to take into
account the needs of both Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Now Saudi Arabia, which along with Egypt are the pivotal Arab
countries, has gone public in support of a tough Arafat position.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Thursday in New York to Arab-American and Muslim
leaders, Abdullah said: ''Jerusalem is important to the hearts of
all Muslims, and in fact it's in the heart of everybody with a
sense of humanity. This is something on which there can be no
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia usually counsels other Arabs privately. That
Abdullah spoke out so strongly in public gave special import to his
message.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, its negotiations with Israel stalled since January, also
publicly backed full Palestinian sovereignty over East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Only Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak apparently is reluctant to
offer wholehearted endorsement to Arafat's position.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has tried to enlist Egypt in a drive
for compromise. Otherwise, what opportunity is left for an accord
between Israel and the Palestinians could be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Muslim Iran's opposition to the peace process, Iranian
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi told British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook on Friday that Tehran wouldn't block a settlement,
according to British officials briefed on their meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In another effort to promote compromise on Friday, Martin Indyk,
the U.S. ambassador to Israel, urged Israel and the Palestinians to
share the Holy City.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no other solution,'' Indyk said at Hebrew Union
College in Jerusalem, where he received an honorary degree. ''It is
not, and cannot, be the exclusive preserve of one religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Indyk, in his second term in the Tel Aviv post after heading the
State Department's Near East bureau, said, ''The solution cannot
come from one side challenging or denying another side's beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador's spokesman, Larry Schwartz, said Indyk was
simply restating U.S. policy that Jerusalem's final status needs to
negotiated by the parties.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton gave a cautious account of the state of play
in an exchange with reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should all wait and see,'' he said. ''Everybody is working
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said there was no reason for despair despite the absence
of breakthroughs in the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   While Albright and U.S. mediator Dennis Ross pressed the
negotiating effort with Israeli and Palestinian officials in New
York, a top Palestinian official, Nabil Shaath, called on Sandy
Berger, Clinton's assistant for security affairs, at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's doable, it's hard, it's difficult,'' he told reporters
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Shaath said, ''once we make some progress'' Clinton may
call another summit meeting, like the one held in July at Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
   But in Ramallah, on the West Bank, Arafat was quoted as telling
the Palestinian Cabinet: ''Israel is not willing to be seriously
engaged in the negotiations and intends to waste more time.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Walker tour:
http://www.state.gov/www/policy--remarks/2000/000824--walker--me.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
