<HEADLINE> Friday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Suicide Epidemic Ravages Native Youth on Northern Ontario Reserves
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A youth suicide epidemic is once again ravaging
northern Ontario's native communities, with one of the worst hit
reporting almost nightly attempts by teen-agers as young as 13 and
14.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty young people have died on reserves across the province's
north this year, Jim Morris, a health adviser to Nishnawbe-Aski
Nation, the region's top native political organization, said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is most serious on the Pikangikum First Nation, a
community about 186 miles northeast of Winnipeg, which made
national headlines when it was rocked by a wave of suicides and
attempts in the summer of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The six suicides among teen-agers since January in Pikangikum
are only ''the tip of the iceberg'' Chief Peter Quill, said in an
interview Friday during a break from an emergency meeting of chiefs
and crisis workers in his troubled community.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the latest spate of deaths shows an alarming new
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're getting younger,'' he said, and more young girls are
now committing suicide, including a group of Pikangikum youths who
recently hanged themselves after sniffing gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ontario has the highest suicide rate in Canada, at
three times the national average, Morris said, and Pikangikum,
Webequie and Kingfisher First Nation have experienced a string of
epidemics since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ------
BCE Has $4 Bil. Alliance with Thomson for Globe and Web Content
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Telecom giant BCE Inc. made another major move to
become Canada's multimedia leader Friday, striking a deal with
Thomson Corp. that combines Canada's biggest private broadcaster,
CTV Inc. and the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The $4 billion alliance, driven by the need to provide more
content for consumers on the Internet, creates a new as-yet-unnamed
company that will be a dominant player in the multimedia world of
broadcasting, newspapers and the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Besides CTV and the Globe, the BCE-Thomson partnership will
control Internet portal Sympatico along with a stable of the
most-visited Canadian Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest in a string of blockbuster ventures that
has shaken up Canada's newspaper, broadcasting and telecom
industries in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, BCE will control the company with a 70.1 per
cent stake. BCE will contribute newly acquired CTV, pending CRTC
approval, and its 71 per cent interest in Internet site
Sympatico-Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson Corp., majority owned by Ken Thomson, will own 20 per
cent and will contribute the Globe and its nine Web sites, along
with a 50 per cent of specialty business news channel ROBTv.
</P>
<P>
   In total, companies controlled by Ken Thomson will own nearly 30
per cent of the new entity.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Hundreds Gather in Montreal To Support Crime Reporter Who Was Shot
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Several hundred people gathered Friday to show
their solidarity for crime reporter Michel Auger, who was shot five
times in the back earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists were joined by other concerned citizens in the
demonstration, which ended in the parking lot of Le Journal de
Montreal, where Auger was shot Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller marches and vigils were held across Quebec and in
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Auger, who often covered biker gangs, released a photo of
himself Friday as a sign of thanks for the support he has received.
It showed the 56-year-old smiling from his hospital bed despite
being hooked up to various tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Paule Beaugrand-Champagne, editor-in-chief of the tabloid, said
Auger was improving and was awake and able to talk with his wife
and a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Helene Pichette, president of the Federation of Quebec
Journalists, said the demonstrations convey the message that
journalists will not be intimidated by the vicious attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''Together . . . we're saying No to intimidation and No to
manipulation,'' she told the crowd of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Police have said they have no information about a motive for the
crime. But Auger's co-workers, who said he has received several
threats over the years, pointed the finger at the criminal groups
he has written about.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Crown Corporation Says B.C. Ferry Followed Regulations
</P>
<P>
   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) -- A 19,000-tonne British
Columbia government passenger ferry was following navigational
regulations when it rolled over a 10-meter power boat, killing one
man and critically injuring a woman, a spokesman for the Crown
corporation said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At least four separate agencies -- Transport Canada, British
Columbia Ferry Corp., the RCMP and the coroner's office -- are
probing Thursday's accident in waters near the Swartz Bay Ferry
Terminal, about 22 miles north of Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Allen Larson, 72, of Port Angeles, Wash., died Thursday
when the massive Spirit of Vancouver Island -- capable of carrying
470 vehicles and more than 2,000 people -- collided with his vessel,
Star Ruby.
</P>
<P>
   His former wife, Lois Larson, 71, of Anchorage, Alaska was
listed in critical condition in the intensive care unit at Victoria
general hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as we know at this point, the ship (ferry) was
complying completely with all regulations that were applicable,''
said Capt. Mike Carter, a British Columbia Ferries vice president.
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia Ferries has no immediate plans to change the
way its vessels leave and enter the waters of Swartz Bay, Carter
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
