<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressJack Cooper:
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST CLEVELAND, Ohio (AP) -- Jack Cooper, a former drummer for
the singing group the O'Jays, died Tuesday after suffering a heart
attack. He was 55.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was the drummer on several O'Jays albums, including
''Live in London,'' released in 1974. He left the group in the
1970s and continued to work in Cleveland area nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Jays, a Philly-style soul vocal trio, released a string of
popular songs during the group's peak years in the 1970s.
Bob Foster:
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Musician Bob Foster, who played steel
guitar at the Grand Ole Opry and on many country music records,
including the first recording session of Patsy Cline, died Tuesday.
He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   Foster had suffered from diabetes and heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a native of Greenville, S.C., moved to Nashville in
1946. He worked first with Red Foley, and went on to play on many
hits, including some by Carl Smith, Kitty Wells, Webb Pierce and
Gene Autry. He performed at the Opry from 1947-1963.
</P>
<P>
   Foster was hired to play on Cline's first recording session,
which resulted in the song ''A Church, A Courtroom and then
Goodbye.''
Jerzy Giedroyc:
</P>
<P>
   MAISONS-LAFFITTE, France (AP) -- Jerzy Giedroyc, a Polish emigre
editor who was widely credited with keeping his country's culture
alive during communist rule, died Thursday night of a heart attack.
He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Giedroyc helped found Kultura, a literary magazine that has been
based outside of Paris since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Idolized by millions of Poles, Giedroyc, as Kultura's
editor-in-chief, worked tirelessly to make the banned writings of
intellectuals and dissidents available in communist Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Kultura printed otherwise unavailable books, such as
Solzhenitsyn's ''Gulag Archipelago'' and Arthur Koestler's
''Darkness at Noon.''
</P>
<P>
   Giedroyc and Kultura achieved legendary status in Poland.
Foreign embassies, Marshal Tito of Yugoslavia, traveling sports
teams and even the Bolshoi theater group helped smuggle Kultura and
books into the Soviet bloc.
Douglas T. Jacobson:
</P>
<P>
   NORTH PORT, Fla. (AP) -- Douglas T. Jacobson, a retired U.S.
Marine who was awarded the Medal of Honor for his valor on Iwo
Jima, died Sunday. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson, who was one of only 11 Medal of Honor recipients
living in Florida, received the honor in 1945 for his service as a
private first class during the World War II battle.
</P>
<P>
   He also served in the Korean and Vietnam wars before retiring as
a major in 1969.
Joe Skubitz:
</P>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- Former U.S. Rep. Joe Skubitz, who
represented the 5th District of Kansas for 16 years, died Monday.
He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   He represented the district from 1963 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Among the things he fought for were benefits for miners
suffering from black lung and to have the old fort at Fort Scott
named a National Historic Site administered by the National Park
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The plaza in front of the site bears his name, in recognition of
his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   His interest in historic preservation also led Skubitz to work
for the establishment of the Piscataway Park across the Potomac
River from Mount Vernon, George Washington's home. Because of the
park, the view from Mount Vernon is much the same as it was when
Washington lived there.
</P>
<P>
   Skubitz also intervened when the Atomic Energy Commission
considered storing atomic waste in Kansas salt mines near Lyons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
