<HEADLINE> Milosevic Steps Up Campaign  </HEADLINE>
By KATARINA KRATOVAC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic stepped
up his re-election campaign with a rally at a factory Friday,
accusing political rivals of being ''Yugoslav traitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The event was Milosevic's second appearance in four days --
unprecedented for the autocratic ruler who rarely shows his face in
public. Opposition analysts say his increased pre-election activity
indicates his concern that he may lose the Sept. 24 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, the Serbian Orthodox Church appealed to Milosevic's
government to end its campaign of ''intimidation'' ahead of the
elections, amid reports of police arresting 22 pro-democracy
activists Friday throughout Serbia. Some were released, but many
remain in detention.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement carried by Beta news agency, the influential Serb
Church's Holy Synod expressed concern about rising political
tensions only days before the vote for Yugoslavia's president,
parliament and municipal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying himself as the patron of reconstruction, Milosevic
traveled to the central Serbian town of Kragujevac to tour the
state-owned Zastava car and military factory, destroyed during NATO
airstrikes last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We shall accomplish everything if we are united. ... Life for
all is possible if we preserve the country from enslavement and
Yugoslav traitors,'' Milosevic said, in his customary reference to
the democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to preserve our freedom and peace from the
missionaries of slavery and war,'' Milosevic told a cheering crowd
of thousands of factory workers, brandishing his picture and waving
Yugoslav flags.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to resist all ''pressures and sanctions by Western
governments seeking to colonize the Balkans and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zastava factory, which had also produced small arms and
artillery, was heavily bombed during the 78-day NATO air campaign
against Yugoslavia in an attempt to end Milosevic's crackdown on
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. The government has vowed to rebuild the
plant, which was forced to stop producing weapons and reduce car
production.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic and his entourage sped into the plant in limousines
with darkened windows while surrounding streets were sealed off by
policemen. No independent media were allowed to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Independent polls show Milosevic trailing behind opposition
candidate Vojislav Kostunica, his chief rival for the crucial
ballot. They suggest Milosevic may be pushed into a runoff for the
country's top post.
</P>
<P>
   The president's visit to Kragujevac came a day after his
supporters pelted Kostunica with tomatoes and stones during a rally
Thursday in a Serb-run enclave in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ''The incident ... shows that Milosevic and the circle around
him are losing power,'' Kostunica said in Belgrade. ''They have no
courage to face me or the people but use a handful of desperate
individuals for a pocketful of coins to bring shame on us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica's ally in Kosovo, Marko Jaksic, named five people, two
of whom are Serbian police officers, as instigators of the incident
in the northern industrial city of Kosovska Mitrovica and said
charges will be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's economy has been shattered by a decade of international
sanctions due to Milosevic's involvement in four Balkan wars.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Human Rights Watch said Friday that
Milosevic's government had turned the election campaign into a
''siege against the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The stakes could not be higher for Milosevic,'' Rachel Denber,
the organization's official for Europe, was quoted in the 10-page
study made available to The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
