<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials express concerns about notification of public  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - As new reports of potentially contaminated
bottled water surfaced Friday, political leaders expressed concerns
about the city's weeklong delay in informing the public about the
possible tamperings.
</P>
<P>
   The city's health department has acknowledged that it was aware
on Sept. 6 of three instances in which bottled water had been
contaminated, although it was not until Sept. 13 that Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani held a press conference to alert the public.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the FBI, not the health department, eventually notified
the police department about the possible tampering. The police in
turn informed the mayor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is troubling to me that the mayor was not informed about
this health issue until almost a week after (health) officials
knew,'' said City Council Speaker Peter Vallone. ''The council's
first concern, of course, is the residents of the city, and their
health was placed in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, as the number of potential contamination cases in the
New York City area reached nine, it remained unclear why the health
department failed to notify top city officials about the suspected
tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Health department spokeswoman Sandra Mullin did not return calls
Friday, but earlier this week, Mullin said she was not sure why the
department did not disclose information about the contaminations
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't really answer those questions,'' she said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Public Advocate Mark Green called for the health
department to disclose why it failed to act once the agency
suspected that bottled water had been tampered with.
</P>
<P>
   ''The health department must reassure the public by immediately
answering these questions,'' said Green. ''Why did it take a week
for the police and the mayor to know about a potential public
health crisis, and why was it the FBI rather than the health
department that finally told them?''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Robles, chair of the City Council's health committee,
also expressed concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''The council will continue to monitor the health department and
all the allegations,'' he said. ''It is definitely cause for
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the three cases the health department knew about, two
other potential cases were reported earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, two new possible cases of tampering in the city were
reported to the police department, although details were not
immediately available. A third case was reported in Hicksville in
Nassau County.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, a 42-year-old woman who bought an 8 oz. bottle of
Poland Spring complained of a burning sensation in her mouth and
nausea.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, police in New Rochelle said that on July 2 a
civilian employee of its department complained of feeling ''a
burning type of sensation'' and becoming ill after he drank from a
half-liter bottle of Poland Spring water he bought at a pizzeria.
</P>
<P>
   Francesco Rizzuti was treated and released from Sound Shore
Hospital in New Rochelle, but due to dizziness has not been back to
work since the incident occurred, said Detective John Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The Westchester County police lab refused to test the bottled
water at the time because there was no suspect or imminent arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The bottle has still not been tested.
</P>
<P>
   In the four instances in which tests have been performed on
contaminated water, authorities identified an ammonia-like
substance in two, lye in one and household bleach in another. Tests
on the other cases have not yet been completed.
</P>
<P>
   The victims have all recovered after short hospitalizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 2153 </TRAILER>
