<DOCNO> APW20000915.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio botches voting age, campaign says Clinton abusing power  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) - Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republican Senate
candidate running against Hillary Rodham Clinton, told an
enthusiastic crowd of elementary students Friday that he wished
they were old enough to vote - but he got the voting age wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''Boy, I wish all of you were 21 years old right now,'' Lazio
said after being welcomed into the Pulaski Street Elementary School
auditorium amid shrieks of approval and applause.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spokesman Michael Marr declined to comment, though the
state Democratic Committee wasted little time in firing off a news
release suggesting Lazio was proposing to repeal the 26th
amendment, which gave the right to vote to 18-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, meanwhile, Lazio's campaign manager said the first
lady is abusing her power by having Senate campaign contributors
stay over at the White House or the Camp David presidential
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ''History is again repeating itself and has reached a new low,''
said Bill Dal Col, referring to criticism of the Clinton
administration after the 1996 re-election campaign for inviting big
donors to spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col said that in addition to releasing the names of recent
overnight guests at the White House and Camp David - something the
White House has agreed to do - the Clinton campaign should ''list
the amount of dollars Mrs. Clinton's guests have contributed to
campaign committees, and to stop this blatant abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the first lady said campaign contributors have been
invited to such sleepovers, but denied the invitations were made in
return for money.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have friends and supporters come and spend time with us and
spend the night with us that we are getting to know and who like
spending time with us,'' she said. ''I don't see what's news about
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
