<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, Sept. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Wins 1st Gold Medal in Sydney
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Firing her way to victory Saturday, American Nancy
Johnson captured the first gold medal of the Sydney Olympics, (Friday night EDT)
in the women's 10-meter air rifle. The silver medal went to Kang Cho-Hyun of
South Korea, while Gao Jing of China took the bronze. It was the first of 13
medal events on Day 1 of full competition.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Deal Met on Debate Formats
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Officials close to negotiations said Democrat Al Gore and
Republican George W. Bush tentatively agreed today on three debate formats --
one traditional two-lectern event, one town hall, and one ''talk show'' forum.
The two campaigns, after meeting 7&AMP;frac12; hours, planned to meet again Saturday
to complete details and sign off on the formats, said one official close to
debate negotiations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Albright: Kharrazi Meeting 'Useful'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Iran's
foreign minister took a small step Friday toward long-sought U.S. diplomatic
contact with Tehran, attending an eight-nation meeting to promote peace in
Afghanistan. The 90-minute meeting was believed to be the first time American
and Iranian officials on such a high level worked together on a specific issue
since the 1979 hostage crisis. ''I think it was a useful meeting,'' Albright
said when asked about the session's significance on U.S.-Iran relations. ''I
think when there are problems to be solved like this together, this is
encouraging.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Philippine Military Raids Rebels
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- Military planes and helicopters pounded the
hills of southern Jolo island Saturday where Muslim rebels are holding 19
foreign and Filipino hostages. Thousands of troops and elite police arrived on
ships to join the rescue attempt. People stood in the streets of Jolo's capital
watching the attack in the distance.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Army To Release Kosovo Report
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army is preparing to publicly release an investigative
report saying several members of the 82nd Airborne Division on peacekeeping duty
in Kosovo beat, threatened and assaulted civilians, officials said. The formerly
classified report also raises questions about the kinds of training these men
received for peacekeeping, the officials said. They discussed the matter on
condition they not be identified.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Al Gore Seeks Black Support
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Appealing to a standing-room-only crowd and a group of
potential voters who overwhelmingly back him, Democrat Al Gore made a campaign
pitch today to students at a historically black university, ''We want Gore! We
want Gore!'' the Howard University audience chanted, waving blue and white
pompoms and Gore-Lieberman signs. With solid black support, the presidential
nominee's focus is boosting turnout among a group that has not gone to the polls
as often as whites.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 160; Nasdaq Sheds 79
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip and tech stocks fell sharply today on a mix of
profit-taking, bargain hunting and general anxiety about corporate profits. The
Dow Jones industrial average closed down 160.47 to 10,927.00. On the NYSE,
losers led gainers by over 5-to-3. The Nasdaq composite index was down 78.63 at
3,835.23.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lawsuits Claim Ritalin 'Conspiracy'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- The makers of Ritalin and the American Psychiatric
Association encouraged overdiagnosis of behavioral disorders in children and
used misleading sales literature to boost sales of the drug, according to a pair
of lawsuits filed this week. Novartis Phamaceutical Corp. and the association
promoted the belief that a large number of children need to take Ritalin for
attention deficit disorder or attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, the
lawsuits filed in New Jersey and California allege. Novartis released a
statement today calling the charges ''unfounded and preposterous'' and said
attention deficit/hyperactivity disorder has been recognized by medical experts
worldwide.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Swiss Wins Gold Medal in Triathlon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Switzerland's Brigitte McMahon outswam the sharks,
bicycled with the pack and outsprinted the field to win the inaugural Olympic
women's triathlon. McMahon, 33, ran away from Australia's Michellie Jones in the
final stretch Saturday (Friday night EDT) to win gold in 2 hours, 40 seconds.
Jones took silver, two seconds behind McMahon, and Switzerland's Magali Messmer
was third.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indiana Trustees Pass Conduct Code
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW ALBANY, Ind. (AP) -- Indiana's trustees adopted a code of conduct today
requiring coaches and athletes to treat others with dignity and respect,
reacting to the behavior that cost Bob Knight his job, . An 11-page report
spelling out the behavior the university expects from participants in its sports
programs was developed by a commission created in May in conjunction with the
zero-tolerance behavior policy Knight agreed to at the time to keep his job.
</P>
