<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Connecticut horses infected with West Nile virus  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - Horses in Danbury, Hebron and Milford
have been diagnosed with the West Nile virus, the first cases of
infection in mammals in the state this year.
</P>
<P>
   The horses in Hebron and Danbury were euthanized on Aug. 30 and
Sept. 7, officials with the state Department of Environmental
Protection said Friday. The horse in Milford became sick on Sept 5,
but is recovering, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No human cases of the mosquito-borne disease have been reported
in Connecticut this summer, but infections have been reported in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The type of mosquito that bit the horses also bites humans,
state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This does mean that the risk is higher now,'' said Dr. Matthew
Cartter, the chief epidemiologist with the state Department of
Public Health. ''It's still low...but it's higher now than it was
throughout the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The DEP on Friday recommended insecticide spraying in a two-mile
radius around the sites where the horses were located. The state
was discussing the spraying with town officials in Danbury,
Milford, Bethel, Hebron Columbia and Lebanon. It would not begin
until Wednesday at the earliest, DEP officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Having three horses sick with WNV in three different parts of
the state, all within a week of each other is a cause for
concern,'' said DEP Commissioner Arthur J. Rocque Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, Theodore Andreadis, who heads the mosquito testing
program at the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station, said
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention may begin testing
Connecticut residents to determine the prevalence of the disease in
humans.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say the risk of infection from West Nile virus is
low. Since most people exposed to the virus show no symptoms, it is
hard to track where and how often the virus is transmitted.
</P>
<P>
   Children, the elderly and people with weakened immune systems
are most at risk.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile virus can cause a range of flu-like symptoms. In the
most serious cases, infection can result in encephalitis, or
swelling of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   A study of antibodies would help determine the risk to humans
from the virus, Andreadis said.
</P>
<P>
   CDC spokesman Tom Skinner said the state would have to initiate
any such study.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they need our assistance, we would help them,'' Skinner
said.
</P>
<P>
   After last year's outbreak in New York City, the CDC went
door-to-door in Queens neighborhoods to collect blood samples.
</P>
<P>
   The survey concluded that between 533 and 1,903 people had been
infected - or 1.2 percent to 4.1 percent of the 46,000 residents in
the neighborhoods tested.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the major questions we're dealing with here is what is
the human risk,'' Andreadis said. ''That's what this survey will
help try to explain to us.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, tests found the virus in human-biting mosquitoes in
Greenwich. The state decided not to spray insecticides, but the
town and the operators of the golf club near where the mosquitos
were trapped sprayed the area Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, about 130,000 mosquitoes have been trapped around
the state and tested at the Agricultural Experiment Station.
Infected bird-biting mosquitoes were found earlier this summer in
Stamford and Norwalk. The state has also found the virus in 279
dead birds in 47 different municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   ''West Nile virus is back with a vengeance this year. It is much
more widespread than any of us expected it would be,'' Andreadis
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-15-00 2207 </TRAILER>
