<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea: Goodwill Begets Goodwill  </HEADLINE>
By SAM F. GHATTAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- North Korea said Friday that it will
welcome any U.S. goodwill gestures, now that the two nations have
resolved a diplomatic flap over the recent body searches of North
Korean delegates.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright sent a message of
regret to North Korea, explaining that the search in a German
airport by American Airlines security personnel did not reflect
U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's No. 2 leader Kim Yong Nam and his delegation
returned to Pyongyang after the incident, skipping last week's
Millennium Summit. North Korean officials denounced the U.S. action
but later said they took note of the American apology.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, in a speech to the annual ministerial meeting of the
General Assembly, North Korea went further.
</P>
<P>
   While calling the recent incident ''the manifestation of the
continued hostile policy'' by the United States, North Korea's U.N.
Ambassador Li Hyong Chol said his nation paid attention ''to the
recently stated U.S. position that it has no reason to perpetuate
its hostile relations with our country.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If this position is put into practice, we will be ready to
respond in a positive way any time,'' Li said.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador also touched on another point of dispute with the
United States, North Korea's missile program, and said it could be
discussed if conditions improve between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the hostile relations are removed and confidence is built
... there will be ways to address the concerns of both sides,'' the
ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
   Li said the issue of reunification of the divided peninsula is
for the North and South Koreans to achieve, independent of any
outside interference.
</P>
<P>
   With growing rapprochement between North and South Korea, he
said the United Nations should dismantle the U.N. Command set up
during the Korean War in 1953, describing it as ''a legacy of the
Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   In veiled criticism of the United States, North Korea said
international peace and security should be achieved by
strengthening the role of the United Nations, ''not by
arbitrariness, high-handedness and intervention of any individual
power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
