<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Won't Meddle With Site  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT LINDLAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- The head of the California
Republican Party said he won't censor the racy offerings available
through a new GOP Web site that sends a piece of online purchases
to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Republicanshopping.com directs visitors to hundreds of different
sites hawking goods and services. But with a few clicks of the
mouse, shoppers can find all manner of books and videos that would
not embody the GOP theme of ''family values.''
</P>
<P>
   At one site, a purveyor of videos, browsers seeking adult movies
can find ''Sexual Chemistry,'' in which ''an overworked chemist
experimenting with new sex-enhancing drug uses himself as a human
guinea pig in order to make an impending deadline. His new drug
works wonders on his libido, but has an unexpected side-effect: it
turns Robert into a Roberta!''
</P>
<P>
   The Penthouse film library is also available, including such
titles as ''Women In and Out of Uniform,'' ''Internet Babes'' and
''Party With the Pets.'' Up to 10 percent of videos' purchase price
goes to the state GOP.
</P>
<P>
   At affiliated site barnesandnoble.com, the full gamut of
grown-up material is available. ''The Anarchists Cookbook,'' an
infamous book on how to build bombs and guns, is there, too. Five
percent of purchases goes to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the offerings were appropriate, California GOP
Chairman John McGraw said the party was keeping an eye on the site.
</P>
<P>
   But, the software entrepreneur said, he was not going to meddle
with business.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have over 400 national merchants in the program,'' McGraw
said at a news conference. ''We vetted every one of those, and if
it comes to our attention that there is some non-acceptable or
pornographic stuff, we will need to review that, and discuss the
course of action.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not change the site after reviewing it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not going to tell people what they can sell, but we are
also not going to promote something that is in-your-face
pornography or anything like that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
