<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> College Rewrites its Loyalty Oath  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL ESKOVITZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- A Communist community college student's refusal
to pledge allegiance to the United States has prompted the college
system to rewrite its loyalty oath requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Fabricio Rodriguez, student body vice president at Mesa
Community College, was denied his minimum-wage salary after he
refused to sign the oath and relinquish his Communist beliefs. The
oath is required of school employees and officers.
</P>
<P>
   After friends and colleagues rallied to Rodriguez's defense,
calling the oath an arcane leftover of the 1950s, the American
Civil Liberties Union took the case.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Maricopa Community College system said it had
eliminated the reference to Communism.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're actually very pleased that the student brought it
forward,'' said college official Rick DeGraw. ''That's what
students are supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The college law has been a state statute since 1961, even though
the U.S. Supreme Court deemed it unconstitutional five years later.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a Cold War relic just like the B-52 bombers,'' said
Hamilton College Prof. Philip Klinkler, who specializes in U.S.
politics and constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
   Klinkler, who said many states had similar provisions designed
to prevent Communist infiltration, said loyalty oaths ''seem pretty
silly'' today.
</P>
<P>
   The rewritten pledge still asks employees to swear allegiance to
the constitution of Arizona and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has not said whether he will sign it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 2253 </TRAILER>
