<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Stock Exchange Chief Resigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The chief executive of the London Stock Exchange
resigned Friday, a casualty of the revolt by shareholders angered
at his efforts to push through a doomed merger with Germany's
Deutsche Boerse.
</P>
<P>
   Gavin Casey stepped down after narrowly surviving a vote by
dissident shareholders on Thursday. He lost at first in a show of
hands but won a follow-up ballot with 53 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Some shareholders had predicted that Casey would resign after
such a rare and potent display of disapproval, but his resignation
was nonetheless an embarrassment for the London exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The LSE is struggling to bounce back from its failure to unite
with the Frankfurt-based Deutsche Boerse and form a powerful
pan-European exchange. At the same time, it is trying to ward off a
hostile takeover bid from Sweden's OM Gruppen, owner of the
Stockholm Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation has mounted that the Frankfurt-based Deutsche Boerse
might launch an unfriendly bid of its own. Other potential bidders
for the LSE include the Nasdaq Stock Market, the technology-rich
U.S. market, and Euronext, which comprises bourses in Paris,
Brussels and Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Upset at what they see as blundering by Europe's largest
exchange, retail brokers and other small investors stalled the
reappointment of Casey and two other LSE directors at Thursday's
annual shareholders' meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Like Casey, the other board members -- chairman Don Cruickshank
and executive chairman Michael Marks -- survived a shareholder vote,
albeit by somewhat wider margins.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is absolutely right that I should resign as chief
executive,'' Casey said in a letter.
</P>
<P>
   Casey has been the LSE's chief executive since 1996. His
resignation is effective immediately, the exchange said.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Marsden, a partner in S.P. Angel and Co., a brokerage and
LSE shareholder, suggested that Casey might have been made a
scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think he did too bad a job. I'm sorry it's come to
this,'' Marsden said.
</P>
<P>
   The London exchange has begun looking for a replacement, and
until then, Cruickshank will shoulder executive responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.londonstockexchange.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
