<HEADLINE> Angels 16, Twins 5  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Tim Salmon matched a career high with his
34th home run and the Anaheim Angels rapped out a season-high 21
hits on their way to a 16-5 win over the Minnesota Twins on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Every starter for Anaheim had at least one hit, as the Angels
scored 16 runs for the second time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took advantage of wildness by Twins starter Matt
Kinney (1-2) and some shoddy fielding in a five-run first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Kinney walked three batters in the inning and threw a wild pitch
that let a run in. In between the wildness, Salmon hit a two-run
shot over the right field wall. Garret Anderson added a two-run
double to put Anaheim up 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels batted around again in the sixth inning, scoring
seven runs. Anderson, who was 3-for-6, collected his 100th RBI of
the season with an RBI single as Anaheim sent 13 men to the plate
to take a 15-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim starter Al Levine allowed only two runs on three hits
but was lifted after four innings, which kept him from winning his
fourth game.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Karl (1-2) came into the game to start the fifth inning,
and pitched two shutout innings to pick up the win.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst outing for Kinney since being called up by the
Twins on Aug. 14. In his first four starts, the right-hander gave
up nine runs in 24 1-2 innings. Friday night Kinney allowed eight
runs on seven hits in one and 1-3 innings, striking out one to go
with his three walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins scored twice in the second on a two-run double by
Corey Koskie to make it 8-2. Jacque Jones drove in two more with a
triple and also scored in the sixth.
Notes@: It took Kinney 24 pitches to record the game's first out.
By then, Anaheim had already scored four runs. ... Darin Erstad
singled twice in the sixth to push his major league-leading hit
total to 218. ... Koskie drove in two runs to give him 59 RBI, one
more than in his rookie season last year. ... Salmon, who hit 34th
homers in 1995, scored three runs to reach 100 for the season,
joining Erstad (106) and Troy Glaus (106). ... Twins pitcher Danny
Mota made his major league debut when he relieved Romero with one
out in the sixth inning. He was acquired by the Twins in the Chuck
Knoblauch trade with the Yankees in 1998. The other three players
picked up by the Twins, Guzman, Brian Buchanan and Eric Milton, are
all on the current roster.
</P>
</TEXT>
