<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor Backs Decree on Police Reform  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA WERNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Talks over reforming the Police Department
took a dramatic turn Friday when Mayor Richard Riordan and Police
Chief Bernard Parks said they would agree to federal oversight of
the department.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan sent a letter to the City Council saying he would
support a consent decree with a few conditions. He had long been
opposed to a decree, under which a federal judge would monitor the
department to make sure it institutes reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's conditions include limiting the monitor's role, said
Kelly Martin, Riordan's chief of staff. Martin also said the mayor
also wants the Justice Department to specify how long a federal
monitor would be in place.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's about-face could be the final step in approval of a
sweeping package of reforms that federal officials have been
hammering out with city negotiators since May with the aim of
making the police department more open and accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's real reform,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have spent more than four years investigating
allegations that the Police Department routinely employs excessive
force and infringes on the rights of minorities. The inquiry
accelerated last fall as a scandal unfolded at the department's
Rampart station.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal involves allegations that police officers beat and
framed innocent people. So far, more than 100 convictions have been
overturned and five officers have been charged with crimes ranging
from planting weapons to attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Justice Department formally told city officials of
its intention to sue over what Washington alleges is a ''pattern of
practice'' of civil rights abuses, prompting the council to open
negotiations with federal attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan and Parks insisted for months that the police force
could reform itself. The mayor adopted his new stance, which has
Parks' support, after negotiations led to a more palatable package
of proposed reforms from the Department of Justice, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also wanted to avoid a federal lawsuit, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement, if accepted by the Justice Department and
approved by the City Council and by Riordan, would eliminate the
threat of a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are pleased with these developments and we look forward to
continuing to work expeditiously toward a final agreement,'' said
Bill Lann Lee, assistant attorney general for civil rights. Lee has
spearheaded negotiations with the city.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Riordan said that besides agreeing to a consent
decree, he will agree to the Police Department keeping data on
traffic stops aimed at determining whether officers engage in
racial profiling. That was a key federal demand that Riordan and
Parks had opposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 2330 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000915.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Launches Sovereignty Study  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Confronting one of the most divisive
issues on the world agenda, Canada has announced the creation of an
independent commission to try to reconcile a country's right to its
sovereignty with the world's duty to intervene to stop atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy used his General Assembly
address Thursday to outline the commission's work and to urge the
188 other countries in the audience -- many of them vehemently
opposed to the concept of ''humanitarian intervention'' -- to join
the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing so threatens the U.N.'s very future as this apparent
contradiction between principle and power, between people's
security and governments' interests, between -- in short --
humanitarian intervention and state sovereignty,'' Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
   The sovereignty vs. intervention debate has grown increasingly
rancorous since Secretary-General Kofi Annan raised it in his
General Assembly address last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Cuba's foreign minister took issue with supporters of
the proposal, saying that such outside intervention in a country's
affairs poses ''the greatest threat to international peace and
security.''
</P>
<P>
   In an address to the General Assembly's ministerial meeting,
Felipe Perez Roque claimed the plan is aimed at poor countries like
Cuba. And he denounced ''humanitarian intervention'' as an attempt
by powerful forces led by the United States and a small group of
its rich allies to fragment and recolonize defenseless developing
nations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said at last week's U.N. Millennium Summit
that ''when good and evil collide'' the international community
must take a side and protect people -- whether by diplomacy,
sanctions or collective force.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the international community met this test last year
when NATO's 78-day bombing campaign ended Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's crackdown on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Western governments have been shamed for having refused to
respond to the Rwandan genocide but also criticized for having
launched airstrikes on Yugoslavia -- violating its sovereignty -- to
protect ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has paralyzed Security Council action in some
conflicts because Russia and China maintain firm positions that a
country's right to deal with its own internal crises, without the
meddling of the international community, is paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Their argument, which is backed by India and many in the
developing world, is based on fear of outside intervention in
hometown conflicts like Chechnya, Tibet and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The International Commission on Intervention and State
Sovereignty will try to address all these issues and more, and come
up with recommendations for how world governments and the United
Nations can confront the next Rwandas and the next Kosovos,
Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which will present its findings and
recommendations to the United Nations in a year, has enlisted
current and former foreign ministers to serve on its political
advisory board. Academics, lawyers and humanitarian experts from
both the developing world and the industrialized world have been
recruited to serve as commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Former Australian Foreign Minister Gareth Evans, co-chairman of
the commission, said that despite the Chinese absence, commission
members would nevertheless solicit input from China.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can't do it in a more publicly involved way, we'll
certainly do it privately,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian government is contributing dlrs 1 million for the
yearlong $2.5 million project, with the Carnegie Corp. of New York,
the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation and the
Rockefeller Foundation also contributing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-15-00 2331 </TRAILER>
