<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-15 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Violated Law in Suicide Case  </HEADLINE>
By TOM STUCKEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- A teen-ager who helped his girlfriend kill
herself last fall violated Maryland's law banning assisted suicide
but was not criminally responsible for his actions, a judge ruled
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Pamela North said it was clear the boy suffered
from serious depression and he could not conform his actions to the
law.
</P>
<P>
   She referred him to a state psychiatric hospital where he will
be evaluated and treated.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, whose name is not being used because he is a juvenile,
was the first person charged under the law passed in 1999 that made
it a crime to help someone commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, then 16, and Jennifer Garvey, 15, took a gun from the
boy's house last September and went to a storm drain known to
neighborhood teen-agers as ''the underworld.'' The two had written
numerous letters to each other in which they talked of how
depressed they were and how they would like to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The boy told police the night of the shooting that he intended
to kill himself, but could not find the gun after his girlfriend
shot herself.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bergeson, an assistant state's attorney, argued that the
evidence did not prove that the boy was unable to control his
actions.
</P>
<P>
   State's Attorney Frank Weathersbee drew criticism from some
legislators for charging the boy under the assisted suicide law,
which they said was never intended to cover a suicide pact.
</P>
<P>
   But North said the law was broadly written and was not limited
to medical personnel or family members who help someone commit
suicide. She said the General Assembly had a chance to change the
law at the 2000 session after the boy was charged but failed to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   North said evidence showed the boy ''did knowingly cause another
person to commit suicide,'' but she said he was not responsible for
his actions because of his history of severe depression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
