<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Neill Latest Yank Forced to Bench  </HEADLINE>
By RONALD BLUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Paul O'Neill is the latest Yankees starter
forced to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The right fielder, bothered by a sore right hip for several
weeks, will be rested for 5-7 games until his hip heals, New York
manager Joe Torre said after Friday night's 11-1 loss to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill didn't play Thursday and was clearly limping Friday,
when he went 0-for-2. He missed six games last month because of the
hip.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees seven games ahead of Boston in the AL East and
just over two weeks remaining, they're looking to get healthy for
the playoffs instead of trying to put their best lineup out every
day.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Bernie Williams hasn't played since Sunday,
allowing his strained right rib cage and sore calf time to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who missed more than a month
with a sore right elbow before returning Sept. 6, sat out Friday
night after feeling pain making a throw to home plate in Thursday
night's 3-2 loss to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to get rid of it in a hurry and I couldn't get on top,''
Knoblauch said. ''It was the first time I had to throw sidearm. It
was a sharp pain, like the pain I had been feeling before.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said Knoblauch was likely to play against the Indians on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it should be all right,'' Knoblauch said. ''I could
probably have played tonight, but Joe said we're looking toward
October. I think it was good just to give it a day to calm down. I
didn't throw today, I just hit. It's not going to go away, but if
it will calm down, I can play with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, who is feeling banged up, was given a night off
and also should be back Saturday. Catcher Jorge Posada was
scheduled to take a day off Friday and will be in Saturday's
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter, however, will be out Saturday. Torre said he
ordered Jeter to take off one of the games during the four-game
series against the Indians and the shortstop chose Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
